{"title_page": "Waveland, Mississippi", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Waveland, Mississippi\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = \"America's Small Beach Town\"<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://waveland.ms.gov/| title=Mayor Mike Smith Welcomes You to the City of Waveland, Mississippi| publisher=City of Waveland| access-date=August 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Hancock_County_Mississippi_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Waveland_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Waveland, Mississippi\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n\n<!-- Location -->\n| subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Mississippi]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Mississippi|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Hancock County, Mississippi|Hancock]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         = 1972\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_28.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 22.36\n|area_land_km2            = 21.99\n|area_water_km2           = 0.37\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 8.63\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 8.49\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.14\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 6435\n|population_density_km2   = 288.97\n|population_density_sq_mi = 748.41\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n| utc_offset = &minus;6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n| utc_offset_DST = &minus;5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 5\n|elevation_ft             = 16\n|coordinates              = {{coord|30|17|23|N|89|23|1|W|region:US-MS_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 39576\n|area_code                = [[Area code 228|228]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 28-78200\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0679394\n|website                  = {{URL|waveland.ms.gov}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 6322\n}}\n[[Image:Mississippi-Coast-towns-NOAA.jpg|thumb|Waveland (left) is west of [[Bay St. Louis, MS|Bay St. Louis]], on the [[Gulf of Mexico]].]]\n\n'''Waveland''' is a city located in [[Hancock County, Mississippi]], United States, on the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. It is part of the [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]]&ndash;[[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]], Mississippi [[Gulfport-Biloxi metropolitan area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]]. The city of Waveland was incorporated in 1972. As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 6,435.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2878200| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001): Waveland city, Mississippi| work=American Factfinder| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| accessdate=August 15, 2017| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213103324/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2878200| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> Waveland was nearly destroyed by [[Hurricane Camille]] on August 17, 1969, and by [[Hurricane Katrina]] on August 29, 2005.\n\nThe current mayor of Waveland is Mike Smith.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waveland-ms.gov/admin.html |title=Waveland, MS Administration |website=Waveland-ms.gov |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041912/http://www.waveland-ms.gov/admin.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Andrew Jackson]] once lived and owned land in Waveland on what is now known as Jackson Ridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usacitiesonline.com/mscountywaveland.htm |title=Waveland Mississippi Profile and Resource Guide, City or community of Waveland, Mississippi Facts, Information, Relocation, Real Estate, Advertising |website=Usacitiesonline.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> Much of Jackson Ridge later became [[Buccaneer State Park]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waveland-ms.gov/about.html |title=About Waveland, MS |website=Waveland-ms.gov |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125155749/http://www.waveland-ms.gov/about.html |archive-date=2015-11-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Silver Slipper Casino (Waveland)|Silver Slipper Casino]] opened on November 9, 2006.\n\n===Hurricane Camille===\nOn August 17, 1969, [[Hurricane Camille]] made landfall at the tip of Louisiana before continuing on shore at Waveland. The storm heavily damaged the areas south of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]]. Recovery efforts went on for nearly a decade. The town later erected a plaque commemorating the efforts of the volunteers who committed time and resources towards rebuilding.\n\n===Hurricane Katrina===\n[[Image:WavelandKatrina.jpg|thumb|Waveland during [[Hurricane Katrina]], August 2005]]\n\nThe city of Waveland was \"ground zero\" of [[Hurricane Katrina]]'s landfall on August 29, 2005. The city received massive damage and is still in the process of recovering and rebuilding. South of the CSXT mainline, the area was almost completely destroyed. The rest of the city took heavy flooding. In a news report, state officials said Waveland took a harder hit from the wind and water than any other town along the Gulf Coast, and that the town was obliterated. 36 years earlier, in 1969, Waveland had been severely damaged by Hurricane Camille.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sciencepolicy.colorado.edu/about_us/meet_us/roger_pielke/camille/report.html |title=Hurricane Camille Report |publisher=Sciencepolicy.colorado.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-05-19}}</ref>\n\nOfficial reports stated that approximately 50 people died when Waveland was hit directly by the eyewall of Katrina and the {{convert|26|ft|m|adj=on}} storm surge. Hurricane Katrina came ashore during the high tide of 8:01AM, +2.2 feet more.<ref>\"2005 NOAA Tide Predictions: Waveland\" (2005), tide on 29-August-2005, ''NOAA'', web: [http://tidesandcurrents.noaa.gov/get_predictions.shtml?year=2005&stn=0551+South+Pass&secstn=Waveland&thh=%2b3&thm=9&tlh=%2b2&tlm=49&hh=*1.28&hl=*1.28 NOAA-tide-tables]</ref>\n\nHurricane Katrina damaged over 40 Mississippi libraries, gutting the Waveland Public Library, as a total loss, requiring a complete rebuild.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hurricane Katrina Related Damages to Public Libraries in Mississippi|date=September 2005|publisher=Mississippi Library Commission|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/cro/katrina/MSPL_Katrina_Damage.pdf}}</ref>\n\n====Recovery====\n[[Image:Waveland City Hall Camille.jpg|thumb|Waveland City Hall plaque to Hurricane Camille recovery volunteers, photo taken July 2006]]\n\nA group of social activists seeking to better the lives of local residents, called the \"[[Rainbow Family]]\", arrived in Waveland soon after Hurricane Katrina. From early September to early December 2005, they ran the \"[[New Waveland Cafe & Clinic]]\"<ref>[http://newwavelandcafe.blogspot.com/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802125650/http://newwavelandcafe.blogspot.com/ |date=August 2, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5025313 |title=Hippie Kitchens Serve Final Meal to Hurricane Victims |publisher=NPR |date=2005-11-23 |accessdate=2013-05-19}}</ref> in the parking lot of Fred's Dept Store on Highway 90. The caf\u00e9 provided free hot meals three times a day. The clinic was staffed by volunteer doctors and nurses from throughout the United States who saw over 5,000 patients during the duration, free of charge and dispensing free medications. Donations of medications and supplies came from a multitude of sources, with International Aid<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.internationalaid.org/ |title=International Aid |publisher=International Aid |date=2013-04-22 |accessdate=2013-05-19}}</ref> arranging the most donations. This was the first experience of the counter-culture Rainbow Family in running a disaster relief center. The Bastrop Christian Outreach Center also volunteered with the Rainbow Family.\n\nWaveland Elementary School, which has served public school students in Grades K-3 (Grades 4-5 attend Second Street Elementary in nearby Bay St. Louis), was heavily damaged by Katrina. The students attending the school were educated in portable classrooms for the beginning of the 2006\u20132007 school year, pending a permanent solution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/08/16/432140225/a-decade-after-katrina-hopes-of-recovery-remain-unfulfilled-in-waveland-miss |title=A Decade After Katrina, Hopes of Recovery Remain Unfulfilled in Waveland, Miss. |date= August 16, 2015 |work=[[NPR News]] |first=Evelina |last=Burnett}}</ref>\n\nThe recovery of Waveland was due in part to the faith-based disaster recovery effort in and around the Waveland area. Shoreline Park Baptist Church in Waveland and Pastor Ed Murphy were vital to this effort, housing and feeding hundreds of missionaries from around the country for many years following Hurricane Katrina in what were referred to as \"Pods for God\". Shoreline Park Baptist Church directed the repair and, in some instances, the rebuilding of homes in the area for many years after the devastation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citizencommandcenter.org/shelters/show/240 |title=Facility: Shoreline Park Baptist Church (CitizenActionTeam.org Database) |website=Citizencommandcenter.org |date=2006-08-10 |accessdate=2017-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117014712/http://www.citizencommandcenter.org/shelters/show/240 |archive-date=2015-11-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tdn.com/lifestyles/until-it-s-done-rainier-man-turned-south-at-memphis/article_76ade591-f11a-5039-98c1-4fb130b7af59.html |title=Until it's done \u2014 Rainier man turned south at Memphis for the mission of his life &#124; Lifestyles |website=Tdn.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nWaveland is in southeastern Hancock County along the shore of [[Mississippi Sound]], an embayment of the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. It is bordered to the north and northeast by the city of [[Bay St. Louis, Mississippi|Bay St. Louis]]. [[U.S. Route 90]] passes through the northern side of the city, leading east across the [[Bay of Saint Louis]] {{convert|18|mi}} to [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]] and west {{convert|55|mi}} to [[New Orleans]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], Waveland has a total area of {{convert|22.4|sqkm|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|22.0|sqkm|order=flip}} are land and {{Convert|0.4|sqkm|order=flip|1}}, or 1.66%, are water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1890= 328\n|1900= 520\n|1910= 554\n|1920= 431\n|1930= 663\n|1940= 768\n|1950= 793\n|1960= 1106\n|1970= 3108\n|1980= 4186\n|1990= 5369\n|2000= 6674\n|2010= 6435\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=6322\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|website=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 6,674 people, 2,731 households, and 1,783 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 980.2 people per square mile (378.4/km\u00b2). There were 3,442 housing units at an average density of 505.5 per square mile (195.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 85.38% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 11.21% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.49% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.50% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.03% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.49% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 0.90% from two or more races. 2.02% of the population were [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 2,731 households out of which 31.4% have children under the age of 18 living with them, 46.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 14.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.7% were non-families. 29.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.7% had someone living alone who is 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.43 and the average family size was 3.01.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 26.0% under the age of 18, 7.5% from 18 to 24, 28.3% from 25 to 44, 23.9% from 45 to 64, and 14.2% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 38 years. For every 100 females, there were 89.9 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 84.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $33,304, and the median income for a family was $38,438. Males had a median income of $29,762 versus $21,694 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $16,413. 13.7% of the population and 11.6% of families were below the [[poverty line]]. Out of the total population, 15.6% of those under the age of 18 and 11.7% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.\n\n==Education==\nWaveland is served by the [[Bay St. Louis-Waveland School District]].\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Johnny Dodds]], jazz clarinetist\n* [[Michael Grimm (musician)|Michael Grimm]], singer; winner of season 5 of ''[[America's Got Talent]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Mississippi}}\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://waveland.ms.gov/ City of Waveland official website]\n* [http://www.mswestcoast.org Mississippi's West Coast], official tourism site\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4491454.stm \"Katrina town fights for survival\"], BBC report, December 2, 2005\n* [http://www.thegivingcircle.org The Giving Circle, Inc.], carrying out Operation: Waveland, MS\n* [http://waylandtowaveland.org Mission to Mississippi], group started in Wayland, Massachusetts to help rebuild Waveland\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110221084635/http://waveland.coastal90.com/ Coastal90 Waveland], local online paper for Waveland post-Katrina\n\n{{Hancock County, Mississippi}}\n{{Mississippi}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Cities in Hancock County, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Gulfport\u2013Biloxi metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Waveland, Mississippi\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = \"America's Small Beach Town\"<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://waveland.ms.gov/| title=Mayor Mike Smith Welcomes You to the City of Waveland, Mississippi| publisher=City of Waveland| access-date=August 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Hancock_County_Mississippi_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Waveland_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Waveland, Mississippi\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n\n<!-- Location -->\n| subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Mississippi]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Mississippi|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Hancock County, Mississippi|Hancock]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         = 1972\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_28.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 22.36\n|area_land_km2            = 21.99\n|area_water_km2           = 0.37\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 8.63\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 8.49\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.14\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 6435\n|population_density_km2   = 288.97\n|population_density_sq_mi = 748.41\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n| utc_offset = &minus;6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n| utc_offset_DST = &minus;5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 5\n|elevation_ft             = 16\n|coordinates              = {{coord|30|17|23|N|89|23|1|W|region:US-MS_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 39576\n|area_code                = [[Area code 228|228]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 28-78200\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0679394\n|website                  = {{URL|waveland.ms.gov}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 6322\n}}\n[[Image:Mississippi-Coast-towns-NOAA.jpg|thumb|Waveland (left) is west of [[Bay St. Louis, MS|Bay St. Louis]], on the [[Gulf of Mexico]].]]\n\n'''Waveland''' is a city located in [[Hancock County, Mississippi]], United States, on the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. It is part of the [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]]&ndash;[[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]], Mississippi [[Gulfport-Biloxi metropolitan area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]]. The city of Waveland was incorporated in 1972. As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 6,435.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2878200| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001): Waveland city, Mississippi| work=American Factfinder| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| accessdate=August 15, 2017| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213103324/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2878200| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> Waveland was nearly destroyed by [[Hurricane Camille]] on August 17, 1969, and by [[Hurricane Katrina]] on August 29, 2005.\n\nThe current mayor of Waveland is Mike Smith.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waveland-ms.gov/admin.html |title=Waveland, MS Administration |website=Waveland-ms.gov |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041912/http://www.waveland-ms.gov/admin.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Andrew Jackson]] once lived and owned land in Waveland on what is now known as Jackson Ridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usacitiesonline.com/mscountywaveland.htm |title=Waveland Mississippi Profile and Resource Guide, City or community of Waveland, Mississippi Facts, Information, Relocation, Real Estate, Advertising |website=Usacitiesonline.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> Much of Jackson Ridge later became [[Buccaneer State Park]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waveland-ms.gov/about.html |title=About Waveland, MS |website=Waveland-ms.gov |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125155749/http://www.waveland-ms.gov/about.html |archive-date=2015-11-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Silver Slipper Casino (Waveland)|Silver Slipper Casino]] opened on November 9, 2006.\n\n===Hurricane Camille===\nOn August 17, 1969, [[Hurricane Camille]] made landfall at the tip of Louisiana before continuing on shore at Waveland. The storm heavily damaged the areas south of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]]. Recovery efforts went on for nearly a decade. The town later erected a plaque commemorating the efforts of the volunteers who committed time and resources towards rebuilding.\n\n===Hurricane Katrina===\n[[Image:WavelandKatrina.jpg|thumb|Waveland during [[Hurricane Katrina]], August 2005]]\n\nThe city of Waveland was \"ground zero\" of [[Hurricane Katrina]]'s landfall on August 29, 2005. The city received massive damage and is still in the process of recovering and rebuilding. South of the CSXT mainline, the area was almost completely destroyed. The rest of the city took heavy flooding. In a news report, state officials said Waveland took a harder hit from the wind and water than any other town along the Gulf Coast, and that the town was obliterated. 36 years earlier, in 1969, Waveland had been severely damaged by Hurricane Camille.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sciencepolicy.colorado.edu/about_us/meet_us/roger_pielke/camille/report.html |title=Hurricane Camille Report |publisher=Sciencepolicy.colorado.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-05-19}}</ref>\n\nOfficial reports stated that approximately 50 people died when Waveland was hit directly by the eyewall of Katrina and the {{convert|26|ft|m|adj=on}} storm surge. Hurricane Katrina came ashore during the high tide of 8:01AM, +2.2 feet more.<ref>\"2005 NOAA Tide Predictions: Waveland\" (2005), tide on 29-August-2005, ''NOAA'', web: [http://tidesandcurrents.noaa.gov/get_predictions.shtml?year=2005&stn=0551+South+Pass&secstn=Waveland&thh=%2b3&thm=9&tlh=%2b2&tlm=49&hh=*1.28&hl=*1.28 NOAA-tide-tables]</ref>\n\nHurricane Katrina damaged over 40 Mississippi libraries, gutting the Waveland Public Library, as a total loss, requiring a complete rebuild.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hurricane Katrina Related Damages to Public Libraries in Mississippi|date=September 2005|publisher=Mississippi Library Commission|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/cro/katrina/MSPL_Katrina_Damage.pdf}}</ref>\n\n====Recovery====\n[[Image:Waveland City Hall Camille.jpg|thumb|Waveland City Hall plaque to Hurricane Camille recovery volunteers, photo taken July 2006]]\n\nA group of social activists seeking to better the lives of local residents, called the \"[[Rainbow Family]]\", arrived in Waveland soon after Hurricane Katrina. From early September to early December 2005, they ran the \"[[New Waveland Cafe & Clinic]]\"<ref>[http://newwavelandcafe.blogspot.com/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802125650/http://newwavelandcafe.blogspot.com/ |date=August 2, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5025313 |title=Hippie Kitchens Serve Final Meal to Hurricane Victims |publisher=NPR |date=2005-11-23 |accessdate=2013-05-19}}</ref> in the parking lot of Fred's Dept Store on Highway 90. The caf\u00e9 provided free hot meals three times a day. The clinic was staffed by volunteer doctors and nurses from throughout the United States who saw over 5,000 patients during the duration, free of charge and dispensing free medications. Donations of medications and supplies came from a multitude of sources, with International Aid<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.internationalaid.org/ |title=International Aid |publisher=International Aid |date=2013-04-22 |accessdate=2013-05-19}}</ref> arranging the most donations. This was the first experience of the counter-culture Rainbow Family in running a disaster relief center. The Bastrop Christian Outreach Center also volunteered with the Rainbow Family.\n\nWaveland Elementary School, which has served public school students in Grades K-3 (Grades 4-5 attend Second Street Elementary in nearby Bay St. Louis), was heavily damaged by Katrina. The students attending the school were educated in portable classrooms for the beginning of the 2006-2007 school year, pending a permanent solution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/08/16/432140225/a-decade-after-katrina-hopes-of-recovery-remain-unfulfilled-in-waveland-miss |title=A Decade After Katrina, Hopes of Recovery Remain Unfulfilled in Waveland, Miss. |date= August 16, 2015 |work=[[NPR News]] |first=Evelina |last=Burnett}}</ref>\n\nThe recovery of Waveland was due in part to the faith-based disaster recovery effort in and around the Waveland area. Shoreline Park Baptist Church in Waveland and Pastor Ed Murphy were vital to this effort, housing and feeding hundreds of missionaries from around the country for many years following Hurricane Katrina in what were referred to as \"Pods for God\". Shoreline Park Baptist Church directed the repair and, in some instances, the rebuilding of homes in the area for many years after the devastation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citizencommandcenter.org/shelters/show/240 |title=Facility: Shoreline Park Baptist Church (CitizenActionTeam.org Database) |website=Citizencommandcenter.org |date=2006-08-10 |accessdate=2017-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117014712/http://www.citizencommandcenter.org/shelters/show/240 |archive-date=2015-11-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tdn.com/lifestyles/until-it-s-done-rainier-man-turned-south-at-memphis/article_76ade591-f11a-5039-98c1-4fb130b7af59.html |title=Until it's done \u2014 Rainier man turned south at Memphis for the mission of his life &#124; Lifestyles |website=Tdn.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nWaveland is in southeastern Hancock County along the shore of [[Mississippi Sound]], an embayment of the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. It is bordered to the north and northeast by the city of [[Bay St. Louis, Mississippi|Bay St. Louis]]. [[U.S. Route 90]] passes through the northern side of the city, leading east across the [[Bay of Saint Louis]] {{convert|18|mi}} to [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]] and west {{convert|55|mi}} to [[New Orleans]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], Waveland has a total area of {{convert|22.4|sqkm|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|22.0|sqkm|order=flip}} are land and {{Convert|0.4|sqkm|order=flip|1}}, or 1.66%, are water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1890= 328\n|1900= 520\n|1910= 554\n|1920= 431\n|1930= 663\n|1940= 768\n|1950= 793\n|1960= 1106\n|1970= 3108\n|1980= 4186\n|1990= 5369\n|2000= 6674\n|2010= 6435\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=6322\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|website=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 6,674 people, 2,731 households, and 1,783 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 980.2 people per square mile (378.4/km\u00b2). There were 3,442 housing units at an average density of 505.5 per square mile (195.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 85.38% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 11.21% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.49% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.50% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.03% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.49% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 0.90% from two or more races. 2.02% of the population were [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 2,731 households out of which 31.4% have children under the age of 18 living with them, 46.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 14.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.7% were non-families. 29.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.7% had someone living alone who is 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.43 and the average family size was 3.01.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 26.0% under the age of 18, 7.5% from 18 to 24, 28.3% from 25 to 44, 23.9% from 45 to 64, and 14.2% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 38 years. For every 100 females, there were 89.9 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 84.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $33,304, and the median income for a family was $38,438. Males had a median income of $29,762 versus $21,694 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $16,413. 13.7% of the population and 11.6% of families were below the [[poverty line]]. Out of the total population, 15.6% of those under the age of 18 and 11.7% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.\n\n==Education==\nWaveland is served by the [[Bay St. Louis-Waveland School District]].\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Johnny Dodds]], jazz clarinetist\n* [[Michael Grimm (musician)|Michael Grimm]], singer; winner of season 5 of ''[[America's Got Talent]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Mississippi}}\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://waveland.ms.gov/ City of Waveland official website]\n* [http://www.mswestcoast.org Mississippi's West Coast], official tourism site\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4491454.stm \"Katrina town fights for survival\"], BBC report, December 2, 2005\n* [http://www.thegivingcircle.org The Giving Circle, Inc.], carrying out Operation: Waveland, MS\n* [http://waylandtowaveland.org Mission to Mississippi], group started in Wayland, Massachusetts to help rebuild Waveland\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110221084635/http://waveland.coastal90.com/ Coastal90 Waveland], local online paper for Waveland post-Katrina\n\n{{Hancock County, Mississippi}}\n{{Mississippi}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Cities in Hancock County, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Gulfport\u2013Biloxi metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Mississippi]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecovery:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2006-2007 \u2192 2006\u20132007", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waveland,_Mississippi"}
