{"title_page": "Tetris", "text_new": "{{About|the 1984 video game}}\n{{short description|tile-matching puzzle video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Tetris\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = AcademySoft\n| publisher = AcademySoft\n| designer = [[Alexey Pajitnov]]\n| platforms = [[Electronika 60]], [[IBM PC]], [[MS-DOS]], Others {{small|(see [[List of Tetris variants]] for other versions)}}\n| released = '''Electronika 60'''{{Video game release|[[Soviet Union|USSR]]|June 6, 1984}}'''MS-DOS''' & '''IBM PC'''{{Video game release|USSR|1986}}\n| genre = [[Puzzle video game|Puzzle]], [[Tile-matching video game|Tile-matching]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Tetris''''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0422\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0441}} {{IPA-ru|\u02c8t\u025btr\u02b2\u026as|}}; [[portmanteau]] of \"[[tetromino]]\" and \"[[tennis]]\") is a [[Tile-matching video game|tile-matching]] [[puzzle video game]] originally designed and programmed by Soviet Russian software engineer [[Alexey Pajitnov]].<ref name=\"tri\">{{Triangulation|273|Dan Ackerman}}</ref> The first playable version was completed on June 6, 1984,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/02/us-videogames-tetris-idUSTRE5510V020090602|work=Reuters|title=At 25, Tetris still eyeing growth|date=June 2, 2009|access-date=July 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106192245/http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/02/us-videogames-tetris-idUSTRE5510V020090602|archive-date=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> while he was working for the [[Dorodnitsyn Computing Centre]] of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union]] in Moscow.<ref>[http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/special/tetrishist.html The Tetris saga] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507094323/http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/special/tetrishist.html |date=May 7, 2012 }}. Retrieved August 24, 2007.</ref> He derived its name from combining the Greek numerical prefix ''[[tetra-]]'' (the falling pieces contain 4 segments) and tennis, Pajitnov's favorite sport.<ref name=\"g4_tetra_tennis\">Pajitnov interview, [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]] \"[[Icons (TV series)|Icons]]\", ep. [http://www.g4tv.com/icons/episodes/1314/Tetris.html 305] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050311025939/http://www.g4tv.com/icons/episodes/1314/Tetris.html |date=March 11, 2005 }}, originally aired on April 22, 2004.</ref><ref name=\"vadim\">Gerasimov, Vadim. [http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm Original Tetris: Story and Download] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821183909/http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm |date=August 21, 2006 }}. June 10, 2007.</ref> The name is also used in-game to refer to the play where four lines are cleared at once.\n\n''Tetris'' was the first game to be exported from the Soviet Union to the United States, where it was published by [[Spectrum HoloByte]] for the [[Commodore 64]] and [[IBM PC]]. The game is a popular use of [[tetromino]]es, the four-element case of [[polyomino]]es, which have been used in popular puzzles since at least 1907. (The name for these figures was given by the mathematician [[Solomon W. Golomb]] in 1953.)\n\nThe game, or [[List of Tetris variants|one of its many variants]], is available for nearly every [[video game console]] and computer [[operating system]], as well as on devices such as [[graphing calculator]]s, [[mobile phones]], [[portable media player]]s, [[Personal digital assistant|PDAs]], [[Internet radio device|Network music players]], and as an [[Easter egg (media)|Easter egg]] on non-media products like [[oscilloscope]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eeggs.com/items/39244.html|title=HP 54600B Oscilloscope Easter Eggs|publisher=Eeggs.com|accessdate=November 12, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217031557/http://www.eeggs.com/items/39244.html|archive-date=December 17, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> It has inspired ''Tetris'' serving dishes,<ref>{{cite news|author=Perets, Abbi|title=Tetris-inspired dishware brings the game to dinner|url=https://www.cnet.com/8301-13553_1-10457461-32.html|work=CNet|date=February 22, 2010|access-date=February 25, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225183821/http://www.cnet.com/8301-13553_1-10457461-32.html|archive-date=February 25, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> and it has even been played on the sides of various buildings.<ref>{{cite magazine| last = Grossman| first = Samantha| title = Watch a Giant Game of Tetris Played on a Philadelphia Skyscraper| magazine = [[Time (magazine)|Time]]| date = April 6, 2014| url = http://time.com/50988/giant-tetris-philadelphia-skyscraper/| accessdate = April 7, 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140406160502/http://time.com/50988/giant-tetris-philadelphia-skyscraper/| archive-date = April 6, 2014| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nWhile versions of ''Tetris'' were sold for a range of 1980s home computer platforms as well as [[Arcade game|arcades]], it was the successful [[Tetris (Game Boy)|handheld version]] for the [[Game Boy]], launched in 1989, that established the game to critics and fans as one of the [[greatest video games of all time]]. {{As of|2011|12}}, the games in the franchise had sold 202{{nbsp}}million copies\u2014approximately 70{{nbsp}}million physical units and 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads\u2014making it one of the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchises of all time]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Tetris basic game.gif|thumb|Video of an open-source ''Tetris'' [[Clone (video game)|clone]]]]\n''Tetris'' is primarily composed of a field of play in which pieces of different geometric forms, called \"[[Tetromino|tetriminos]]\", descend from the top of the field.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} During this descent, the player can move the pieces laterally and rotate them until they touch the bottom of the field or land on a piece that had been placed before it.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\">{{cite web |url=https://tetris.com/about-us |title=About ''Tetris'' |publisher=The Tetris Company |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref> The player can neither slow down the falling pieces nor stop them, but can accelerate them in most versions.<ref>''Tetris'' (Game Boy) instruction booklet, p. 4</ref><ref>''Tetris DS'' instruction booklet, p. 6</ref> The objective of the game is to use the pieces to create as many horizontal lines of blocks as possible. When a line is completed, it disappears, and the blocks placed above fall one rank.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> Completing lines grants points, and accumulating a certain number of points moves the player up a level, which increases the number of points granted per completed line.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\">''Tetris'' (Game Boy) instruction booklet, p. 16</ref> In most versions, the speed of the falling pieces increases with each level, leaving the player with less time to think about the placement.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> The player can clear multiple lines at once, which can earn bonus points in some versions.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} It is possible to complete up to four lines simultaneously with the use of the I-shaped tetrimino; this move is called a \"Tetris\", and is the basis of the game's title.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\"/> If the player cannot make the blocks disappear quickly enough, the field will start to fill, and when the pieces reach the top of the field and prevent the arrival of additional pieces, the game ends.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> At the end of each game, the player receives a score based on the number of lines that have been completed.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\"/> The game never ends with the player's victory; the player can only complete as many lines as possible before an inevitable loss. However, in some versions of the game, the player can achieve a \"max-out\" by reaching the highest score that can be displayed (999,999 on a six-digit display).{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} \n\nSince 1996, The Tetris Company has internally defined specifications and guidelines that publishers must adhere to in order to be granted a license to ''Tetris''. The contents of these guidelines establish such elements as the correspondence of buttons and actions, the size of the field of play, the system of rotation, and others.<ref name=\"HistoryOfTetris\">{{cite web |url=https://tetris.com/history-of-tetris |title=History of ''Tetris'' |publisher=The Tetris Company |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"tftt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/interview/11267/tetris-from-the-top-an-interview-with-henk-rogers |title=''Tetris'' from the Top: An Interview with Henk Rogers |author=Metts, Jonathan |website=Nintendo World Report |date=April 6, 2006 |accessdate=April 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Game pieces===\n[[File:Tetrominoes IJLO STZ Worlds.svg|thumb|left|All seven tetriminos using the standard color scheme]]\nThe pieces on which the game of ''Tetris'' is based around are called \"tetriminos\". Pajitnov's original version for the [[Electronika 60]] computer used green brackets to represent the blocks that make up tetriminos.<ref name=\"vadim\"/> Versions of ''Tetris'' on the original Game Boy/Game Boy Color and on most dedicated handheld games use [[monochrome]] or grayscale graphics, but most popular versions use a separate color for each distinct shape. Prior to The Tetris Company's standardization in the early 2000s, those colors varied widely from implementation to implementation.\n\n===Scoring===\nThe scoring formula for the majority of ''Tetris'' products is built on the idea that more difficult line clears should be awarded more points. For example, a single line clear in ''Tetris Zone'' is worth 100 points, clearing four lines at once (known as a ''Tetris'') is worth 800, while each subsequent back-to-back ''Tetris'' is worth 1,200.<ref name=\"tzmanual\">[http://zone.tetris.com/page/manual ''Tetris Zone'' manual] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206023148/http://zone.tetris.com/page/manual |date=February 6, 2009 }} as of November 12, 2008</ref> In conjunction, players can be awarded combos that exist in certain games which reward multiple line clears in quick succession. The exact conditions for triggering combos, and the amount of importance assigned to them, vary from game to game.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nNearly all ''Tetris'' games allow the player to press a button to increase the speed of the current piece's descent or cause the piece to drop and lock into place immediately, known as a \"soft drop\" and a \"hard drop\", respectively. While performing a soft drop, the player can also stop the piece's increased speed by releasing the button before the piece settles into place. Some games only allow either soft drop or hard drop; others have separate buttons for both. Many games award a number of points based on the height that the piece fell before locking, so using the hard drop generally awards more points.\n\n=== Easy spin dispute ===\nAlthough not the first ''Tetris'' game to feature a new kind of ''Tetris'', \"easy spin\" (see ''[[The Next Tetris]]''), also called \"infinite spin\" by critics,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gba/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html |title=Tetris Worlds for Game Boy Advance Review |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=September 5, 2001 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028130427/http://www.gamespot.com/gba/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html |archive-date=October 28, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Tetris Worlds]]'' was the first game to fall under major criticisms for it. Easy spin refers to the property of a Tetromino to stop falling for a moment after left or right movement or rotation, effectively allowing someone to suspend the Tetromino while thinking on where to place it. This feature has been implemented into [[The Tetris Company]]'s official guideline.<ref name=\"tftt\"/> This type of play differs from traditional ''Tetris'' because it takes away the pressure of higher level speed. Some reviewers<ref name=\"gsrev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html|title=Tetris Worlds for PlayStation 2 Review|accessdate=November 12, 2008|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 19, 2002|author1=Jeff Gerstmann|author2=Ryan Davis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130070533/http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html|archive-date=January 30, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> went so far as to say that this mechanism broke the game. The goal in ''Tetris Worlds'', however, is to complete a certain number of lines as fast as possible, so the ability to hold off a piece's placement will not make achieving that goal any faster. Later, GameSpot received \"easy spin\" more openly, saying that \"the infinite spin issue honestly really affects only a few of the single-player gameplay modes in ''Tetris DS'', because any competitive mode requires you to lay down pieces as quickly as humanly possible.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ds/puzzle/tetris/review.html |title=Tetris DS for DS Review \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=March 20, 2006 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805040528/http://www.gamespot.com/ds/puzzle/tetris/review.html |archivedate=August 5, 2011 |df= }}</ref> In response to the issue, [[Henk Rogers]] stated in an interview that infinite spin was an intentional part of the game design, allowing novice players to expend some of their available scoring time to decide on the best placement of a piece. Rogers observed that \"gratuitous spinning\" does not occur in competitive play, as expert players do not require much time to think about where a piece should be placed. A limitation has been placed on infinite lock delay in later games of the franchise, where after a certain amount of inputs i.e.: rotations and movements, the piece will instantly lock itself. This is defaulted to 15 inputs.<ref name=\"tftt\"/>\n\n== History ==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width    = 250\n | image1   = Tetris-VeryFirstVersion.png\n | caption1 = The first version of ''Tetris'', completed in 1984, run on an emulator of the [[Electronika 60]]\n | image2   = Tetris DOS 1986.png\n | caption2 = Screenshot of the 1986 IBM PC version developed by Dmitry Pavlovsky and [[Vadim Gerasimov]]\n | image3   = Tetris screenshot (Amiga, Infogrames).png\n | caption3 = The version designed by Spectrum Holobyte contained Russia-related images (Amiga version screenshot, 1988)\n}}\n\n=== Creation and early popularity ===\n''Tetris'' was created in June 1984 by [[Alexey Pajitnov]], an [[artificial intelligence]] researcher working for the [[Soviet Academy of Sciences]] (now the Russian Academy of Sciences) at the Computer Center in Moscow.<ref name=\"guardian2014\">{{cite news |author=Phil Hoad |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jun/02/how-we-made-tetris |title=Tetris: how we made the addictive computer game &#124; Culture |newspaper=The Guardian |date=June 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621140034/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jun/02/how-we-made-tetris |archive-date=June 21, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Tasked with testing the capabilities of new hardware, Pajitnov would do so by writing simple games for them. He initially considered creating a game around [[pentomino]]es, which featured in puzzle games that he had enjoyed as a child, but felt that it might have been too complicated with twelve different shape variations, so the concept switched to [[tetromino]]es, of which there are seven variants.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /> The [[Electronika 60]] computer used to develop the game had only a text-based display, so the tetrominoes had to consist of pseudo-graphics.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /> Realizing that completed lines resulted in the screen filling up quickly, Pajitnov decided to delete them, creating a key part of ''Tetris'' gameplay.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" />\n\nPajitnov's game proved popular with his colleagues.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /> Academy of Sciences co-workers Dmitry Pavlovsky and [[Vadim Gerasimov]] ported the game to the [[IBM Personal Computer|IBM PC]]. Gerasimov reports that Pajitnov chose the name ''Tetris'' as \"a combination of '[[tetromino]]' and 'tennis'\". From there, the PC game became popular and began spreading around Moscow.<ref name=\"vadim\"/> Unsure of how to publish his game and fearful of the response of the Soviet regime if he did so, Pajitnov took the opportunity offered by [[Perestroika]] and gave the rights to the Soviet government for ten years.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /><ref name=\"alexyinterview\">Boyes, Emma. [http://www.gamespot.com/news/6181946.html Q&A Tetris creator Alexey Pajitnov] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607193954/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6181946.html |date=June 7, 2009 }}. Retrieved October 31, 2007.</ref>\n\n=== Exportation and licensing ===\nPajitnov's boss at the Soviet Academy shared a copy with some colleagues at the SCKI Institute of Computer Science in [[Budapest]], Hungary, where it was ported to the Commodore 64 and Apple II by some of its students. It was at the institute where ''Tetris'' was \"discovered\" by Robert Stein, a man who ran a British software company named Andromeda Software. Stein asked the Institute's director about licensing, and the director told him that the game had come from the Soviet Union. The director had the number to the Soviet Academy's [[Telex]] machine, and Stein used the number to send a message stating that he wanted to acquire the rights to ''Tetris''. The message was forwarded to Pajitnov, and after several weeks of getting translations and proper authorization, Pajitnov sent a reply suggesting that he was interested in a deal. Stein interpreted this as a verbal agreement for him to sub-license ''Tetris'' rights, and he began to make deals with [[Mirrorsoft]] and [[Spectrum HoloByte]] that would allow the latter two to publish ''Tetris'' for computers in their respective regions. There was a problem, however: Stein did not have a signed contract with the Soviet Union. Stein sent a second Telex message to the Academy with his offer for ''Tetris'', and Pajitnov gave a vague, yet positive response. Stein continued to push for a deal with the Soviet Union, but while he was doing so, the Soviet Academy had intervened with the negotiations. The Academy's internal publishing and licensing group, AcademySoft, handled further negotiations with Stein. AcademySoft insisted that the only rights available were the IBM PC rights, and Stein agreed; he would negotiate for future ''Tetris'' rights later.<ref name=\"stts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_fQtxKmgJC8|title=The Story of Tetris}}</ref>\n\nSeveral months had passed since Stein found ''Tetris'' at the Hungarian Institute, and Stein still did not have a signed contract with the Soviet Union for any ''Tetris'' rights. Stein sent a Telex message to the Soviet Union in April 1987 stating that Mirrorsoft and Spectrum HoloByte were going to release their versions of ''Tetris'', but his forcefulness would get him nowhere. Mirrorsoft and Spectrum HoloByte had prepared their versions of ''Tetris'' for release under the assumption that Stein had secured all the rights with the Soviet Union, and Stein finalized his deals with the two companies in June 1987.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\n=== ''Tetris'' is released ===\nSome time before Mirrorsoft's and Spectrum HoloByte's versions of ''Tetris'' were released, Stein received a Telex message from another Soviet organization known as [[Elektronorgtechnica]] (\"Elorg\"). The message stated that Stein was selling ''Tetris'' illegally, and that further negotiations would have to go through them. Elorg learned that researchers at the Soviet Academy, including Pajitnov, were developing computer programs. Elorg met with Pajitnov to see if any of his programs could be sold internationally, and Pajitnov casually mentioned his ''Tetris'' dealings during the meeting. This shocked the Elorg representatives; they demanded that all of the paperwork be handed over immediately and they took over the ''Tetris'' negotiations. Stein flew to Moscow to explain himself at Elorg's request, and the two continued negotiations.<ref name=\"stts\"/> Although nothing was signed with the Soviet Union yet, the computer versions of ''Tetris'' were released in January 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/29/business/new-software-game-it-comes-from-soviet.html|title=New Software Game: It Comes From Soviet|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=1988-01-29}}</ref> The Commodore 64 version had a 26-minute soundtrack composed by game musician Wally Beben. The game's popularity was tremendous; ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' called the game \"deceptively simple and insidiously addictive\".<ref name=\"CGW\">{{Cite news|date=May 1988|last=Wagner|first=Roy| periodical=Computer Gaming World|title=Puzzling Encounters|pages=42\u201343}}</ref> Stein eventually got a deal with Elorg on May 10, 1988.<ref name=\"tl\"/> The deal gave Andromeda the rights to ''Tetris'' for home computers and \"different types of computers\"; the second line was vague enough for Stein to assume that it also referred to systems other than home computers. Stein contacted Mirrorsoft to tell them that the deal was done, and Mirrorsoft inquired about other rights to ''Tetris''. Stein told them that future deals would be coming.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\n=== Henk Rogers enters the picture ===\n[[Henk Rogers]] was first exposed to ''Tetris'' while he was visiting the [[Consumer Electronics Show]] (CES) in Las Vegas in January 1988. Phil Adam, the president of Spectrum HoloByte, stood on the showroom floor displaying ''Tetris'' to a line of attendees that included Rogers. Although Rogers considered ''Tetris'' to be the quietest game at the show, he was eventually hooked and pursued the rights to the game. Rogers learned that Gilman Louie, the CEO of Spectrum HoloByte, was going to Japan to try to shop the game. Louie pitched ''Tetris'' to [[ASCII]], but they turned it down, thinking it was \"too retro\". Louie eventually found Rogers and the two signed a letter of intent for Rogers' company, [[Blue Planet Software|Bullet-Proof Software]], to publish Tetris in Japan for every platform Rogers could think of, including [[Nintendo]]'s Famicom. Later on, Louie contacted Rogers to tell him that while he could have the Japanese home computer rights to Tetris, he would have to contact [[Atari Games]] if he wanted the Famicom and Japanese arcade rights. Engineers at Atari Games got addicted to the PC version of ''Tetris'', and that encouraged the company to get the console and arcade rights from Mirrorsoft in exchange for the PC rights to ''[[Blasteroids]]''. Atari Games initially declined to sub-license any rights to Rogers when he first contacted them. Despite this, Rogers flew out to California and camped out in the Atari Games parking lot, waiting for an opportunity to talk to its president, Hideyuki Nakajima. One day as Nakajima was leaving, Rogers made his pitch to him. After hearing it, Nakajima agreed to a meeting. The two had a meeting over a sushi dinner, and at the meeting, Nakajima told Rogers that while the Famicom rights were up for grabs, he couldn't have the Japanese arcade rights since they were already sold to [[Sega]]. Steve Hanawa, a representative of Sega of America at the time, learned about ''Tetris'' during the development of ''Monopoly''; the team developing the title was also developing a PC version of ''Tetris'', and Hanawa's addiction to the game led him to get Sega of Japan to license the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sega-16.com/2011/10/interview-steve-hanawa/|title=Interview: Steve Hanawa (SOA Director of R&D}}</ref> Regardless, Rogers paid Atari $300,000 for the Famicom rights.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nBullet-Proof Software had initially only received about 40,000 orders. Henk Rogers contacted [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]], the president of Nintendo at the time, in hopes that he could help him advertise the title. Yamauchi was interested, so he passed down Tetris to [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]. Days later, Yamauchi sent a letter to Miyamoto asking if Tetris was a good game. Miyamoto said it was, and when Yamauchi asked why, Miyamoto said, \"Because your accountants and secretaries are playing it\". After this happened, Yamauchi agreed to push sales of Tetris. Orders increased from 40,000 to over 200,000.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nBullet-Proof Software's home computer versions of ''Tetris'' were released on November 18, 1988,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000823075838/http://www.bps.co.jp/04_products/index71.html|title=Products: Personal Computers|publisher=Bullet-Proof Software}}</ref> while the Famicom version was released on December 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000823075808/http://www.bps.co.jp/04_products/index31.html|title=Products: Family Computer|publisher=Bullet-Proof Software}}</ref> The Famicom version would go on to sell over 2 million copies in Japan,<ref name=\"hist\"/>\n\nSega's arcade version for [[Sega System 16]] and System E arcade boards were released in December 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sega-interactive.co.jp/product/9260|title=\u30c6\u30c8\u30ea\u30b9|publisher=Sega}}</ref><ref>{{KLOV game|10082|Tetris (Sega)}}</ref> It won the Japanese [[Gamest]] Award for [[Game of the Year]] the following year, and it was number-three in ''[[Famitsu|Famicom Ts\u016bshin]]''{{'}}s August and September 1989 arcade earnings charts.<ref>''[[Famitsu|Famicom Ts\u016bshin]]'', issue 19 (September 15, 1989)</ref> It rose to number two in October 1989, overtaking [[Namco]]'s [[racing video game]] ''[[Winning Run]]''.<ref>''[[Famitsu|Famicom Ts\u016bshin]]'', issue 22 (October 27, 1989)</ref>\n\n=== Licensing issues ===\n{{main|Tetris (NES video game)|Tetris (Game Boy video game)}}\nIn December 1988, Rogers met with the president of Nintendo of America at the time, [[Minoru Arakawa]] at NOA's headquarters to discuss the possibility of ''Tetris'' being one of the launch titles for the upcoming [[Game Boy]]. Arakawa was intrigued; he was aware of the success of the Famicom version of ''Tetris'' in Japan. Rogers contacted Robert Stein under the assumption that he had the handheld rights and offered him $25,000 in advance for them. While this was happening, Mirrorsoft had contacted Stein to see if he could give them those same rights. Stein was wishy-washy with his response; he told Rogers that he would have to check with Elorg.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nAs time passed, Rogers grew suspicious of Stein and then got word that Gilman Louie was trying to sell the handheld rights to Nintendo. When Arakawa contacted Rogers about it, Rogers told him that Louie didn't actually have the handheld rights and that he needed Arakawa to give him a chance to finalize the deal. Figuring it would be easier to talk to Elorg himself to try to get the handheld rights instead of waiting for Stein to get back to him, Rogers headed to Elorg's headquarters. When Mirrorsoft caught wind of Nintendo's interest in the handheld rights to ''Tetris'', their parent company, the Maxwell Corporation, sent its joint managing director Kevin Maxwell to Elorg's headquarters.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nOn February 22, 1989, Stein, Rogers, and Maxwell headed to Elorg's headquarters to negotiate with Elorg about the handheld rights to Tetris. While Stein and Maxwell booked meetings with Elorg in advance, Rogers did not. Rogers was the first to arrive there; he asked someone at Elorg about who he could talk to about Tetris as soon as he arrived. He was directed to Nikolai Belikov, Elorg's managing director. Belikov had been hired by Elorg to sort out the licensing problems for ''Tetris''; Elorg was not getting paid. Rogers introduced himself by taking out a copy of the Famicom version of ''Tetris'' and said that he was the \"biggest publisher of Tetris in the world\". To Rogers' shock, Belikov told him that Elorg had not given any console rights to ''Tetris'' to anyone. Rogers told Belikov about the chain of licensees that fot him the rights, but Belikov told him that Elorg only gave the rights to Tetris to Andromeda Software, and that those rights were for home computers. After some discussion, Rogers and Belikov set up a meeting for the following day.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nStein's meeting with Belikov was scheduled to start, and Rogers had barely missed Stein as he was leaving. Stein had planned the meeting with the intent of getting the handheld rights to Tetris. However, what happened instead was that Belikov added an amendment to the contract between Elorg and Andromeda and that Stein agreed to look over the amended contract for a few days. The meeting with Maxwell began after Stein had left. Belikov showed Maxwell a copy of the Famicom version of ''Tetris'' and asked him what it was. Maxwell said that it may be a pirated version. The meeting resulted in Mirrorsoft getting a right of first refusal to any new rights to ''Tetris'', and it was confirmation for Elorg that the console rights to ''Tetris'' were never given to anyone.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nOn February 23, 1989, the scheduled meeting between Rogers and Elorg began. The two parties were at opposite ends of a long table; Rogers was on one end while Belikov, Tetris creator Alexey Pajitnov, and other Elorg members were on the other end. Rogers started things off by giving the Elorg members a \"crash course\" of the video game market. After that, Elorg showed Rogers the original contract they had with Robert Stein of Andromeda Software. Rogers looked through it and found the line that had caused the licensing issues - the contract stated that Andromeda had the rights to Tetris for \"different types of computers\". Stein assumed that this also meant things like game consoles. After that, Rogers offered the Elorg members a fixed amount of money for each cartridge sold. Belikov asked Rogers to make a formal offer for the handheld rights after hearing the other offer. Stein met up with Belikov that same day with the signed contract, but Belikov stated that Elorg was not ready to hand over the handheld rights to Tetris yet. Rogers met up with Belikov a day later with the formal offer and gave it a one-week deadline.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nSometime later, Belikov contacted Rogers to tell him that Maxwell was bidding for the handheld rights. Rogers told Belikov that although he couldn't give him as much money as Maxwell, he could at least give him honesty and the promise to pay for each cartridge. Several days later, Rogers presented Elorg with a finalized contract and walked through its details. Belikov signed it, and it resulted in Rogers and Nintendo getting the handheld rights to Tetris.<ref name=\"stts\"/> The results of the licensing deal put Bullet-Proof Software as a licensor and Nintendo as a sub-licensor. On top of that, ''Tetris'' had been bundled with every Game Boy.<ref name=guardian020609/> Rogers later said, \"''Tetris'' made Game Boy and Game Boy made ''Tetris''.\"<ref name=\"guardian2014\" />\n\n=== Legal battles ===\n{{main|Tetris (Atari)}}\nAfter Henk Rogers successfully got the handheld rights to ''Tetris'', Elorg told him they would like for him to make an offer for the console rights to ''Tetris''. There would be trouble ahead: Mirrorsoft had the right of first refusal to any new rights to ''Tetris'', and Atari could potentially go after Rogers if they found out a deal was being made. When Rogers left Moscow, he contacted Nintendo to tell them that the console rights were available. Nintendo told Rogers to go back to Moscow with their offer of $5 million in advance and to contact them if he thinks a deal could happen. As soon as Nintendo found out a deal was possible, Minoru Arakawa and [[Howard Lincoln]] headed to Elorg's headquarters to secure the console rights. As soon as Nintendo got them, they sent a cease-and-desist letter to Atari Games.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nDespite the letter, Atari Games went through with releasing their NES version of ''Tetris'' through their subsidiary, [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]]. They distributed it under the name ''TET\u042fIS: The Soviet Mind Game'' (with [[faux Cyrillic]] typography incorporating the [[Ya (Cyrillic)|Cyrillic letter Ya]]). Atari Games sued Nintendo, believing they had the rights. After four weeks on the shelf, the courts ruled that Nintendo was the only company which had the rights to ''Tetris'' on home game systems. The amended contract with Andromeda had invalidated any \"console rights\" given out. Tengen's ''TET\u042fIS'' was recalled with an unknown number of copies sold.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=From Russia with Litigation|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=26|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=February 1997|page=42}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|year=2002|title=The Wish List|journal=Edge Presents Retro|id=|url=|quote=}}</ref>\n\nSega had planned to release a [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive]] version of ''Tetris'' on April 15, 1989, but they cancelled its release<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19890501p.pdf#page=14|title=Game Machine: \"Nintendo Offers Home Video Game 'Tetris'\"|publisher=Amusement Press|date=1989-05-01}}</ref> during Atari's licensing issues, resulting in fewer than ten copies being printed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/you-could-own-this-copy-of-tetris-for-only-1-000-000-5822380 |title=You Could Own This Copy of Tetris for Only $1,000,000 |first=Michael |last=McWhertor |work=Kotaku |date=July 18, 2011 | access-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604193847/https://kotaku.com/you-could-own-this-copy-of-tetris-for-only-1-000-000-5822380 |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A new port of the arcade version by M2 was included in the [[Sega Genesis Mini]] microconsole, released in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/06/04/final-12-genesis-mini-games-list-includes-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-versions-of-tetris |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604221811/https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/06/04/final-12-genesis-mini-games-list-includes-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-versions-of-tetris |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tetris NES play.png|thumb|right|250px|A-Type game screenshot of the official [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] version of ''Tetris'']]\nNintendo released their NES version of ''Tetris'' in November 1989. It sold 8 million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"tl\">{{Cite episode | title = Tetris: From Russia With Love | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0074pz0 | series = BBC Four | credits = Director/Producer: Magnus Temple; Executive Producer: Nick Southgate | network = [[BBC]] | station = [[BBC Four]] | date = 2004 | time = 51:23 | quote = The real winners were Nintendo. To date, Nintendo dealers across the world have sold 8 million ''Tetris'' cartridges on the Nintendo Entertainment system. | access-date = September 4, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160101183339/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0074pz0 | archivedate = January 1, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref>  Nintendo's NES version lacked the side-by-side 2-player option featured in Tengen's version. ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' reviewed this version in its November / December 1989 edition. The [[Classic Tetris World Championship]] commenced in 2010 and uses the Nintendo version of ''Tetris''.\n\nNintendo released the game again for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System ([[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]]) along with [[Dr. Mario]]. The new version used different colors than older versions, and makes the squares look more connected. This version is similar to the version released on the NES.\n\n=== The Tetris Company ===\n{{Main|The Tetris Company}}\nIn 1996, the rights to the game reverted from the Russian state to Pajitnov himself, who previously had made very little money from the game.<ref name=guardian020609/> That year, [[The Tetris Company]] was founded, claiming to hold [[copyright registration]]s for ''Tetris'' products in the U.S.<ref>Blue Planet Software, Inc. v. Pajitnov, 334 F. Supp 2d 425 (S.D.N.Y. 2004).</ref><ref>See, e.g., Copyright Registration Nos. PAu 1-214-036; PAu 1-214-035; PA 412\u2013169; PA 412\u2013170, among others.</ref> and taking out trademark registrations for ''Tetris'' in almost every country in the world.<ref>See, e.g., Trademark Registration Nos. 1,753,062 (USA); 1,657,499 (USA); 1,742,325 (USA); 1,382,544 (UK); 1,382,543 (UK); 507644 (Taiwan); 498703 (Taiwan); 098,381 (Peru); 097, 244 (Peru); 266/36 (Saudi Arabia), among others.</ref> They have licensed the brand to a number of companies, and the U.S. Court of International Trade and the U.S. Customs have at times issued seizure orders to preclude unlicensed ''Tetris''-like games from being imported into the U.S.,<ref>See [https://web.archive.org/web/20090827075506/http://www.cit.uscourts.gov/slip_op/Slip_op00/00-27.pdf Luxury Int\u2019l, Inc. v. U.S., No. 99-02-00093, Slip Op. 00-27] (Ct. Int\u2019l Trade 2000), holding that Luxury violated Customs' administrative procedure; U.S. Customs Service Memorandum Order, ENF-4-02-RR:IT:IP 470343 GFM (December 19, 2000); U.S. Customs Service Memorandum Order, ENF4-02-RR:IT:IP 469107 GFM (July 31, 2000).</ref> though bulletins circulated by the U.S. Copyright Office state that copyright does not apply to the rules of a game.<ref name=\"17usc102\">U.S. Copyright Office. [http://www.copyright.gov/title17/92chap1.html Title 17, United States Code, section 102] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518093808/http://www.copyright.gov/title17/92chap1.html |date=May 18, 2011 }}. Retrieved March 12, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"fl108\">U.S. Copyright Office. [http://www.copyright.gov/fls/fl108.pdf \"Publication FL-108: Games.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625004618/http://www.copyright.gov/fls/fl108.pdf |date=June 25, 2009 }} June 2008. Explanation of how {{usc|17|102}}(b) limits the extent to which copyright applies to the rules of a game. Retrieved June 2, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn late 1997<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abednarz.net/wp/category/tetris-copyright/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123070027/http://abednarz.net/wp/category/tetris-copyright/ |url-status=dead|archive-date=January 23, 2009 |title=The Tetris Company's Activities |author=Bednarz, Andrew James |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |df= }}</ref> and mid-2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expertreviews.co.uk/general/90129/tetris-blocks-mac-quinn-game |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006212333/http://www.expertreviews.co.uk/general/90129/tetris-blocks-mac-quinn-game |url-status=dead|archive-date=October 6, 2011 |title=Tetris blocks Mac Quinn game |date=July 11, 2006 |publisher=Expert Reviews |author=Aughton, Simon |accessdate=June 23, 2012}}</ref> TTC's legal counsel sent [[cease and desist]] letters to Web sites on the basis of ''Tetris''-type games infringing the \"Tetris\" trademark, [[trade dress]], and/or \"[[look and feel]]\" copyright. Gerasimov removed his 1988 version of the game from his website in October 2003, in response to a demand from counsel for The Tetris Company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vadim.www.media.mit.edu/tetris.htm|title=Tetris: the story|date=November 28, 2003|accessdate=September 18, 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031128090208/http://vadim.www.media.mit.edu/tetris.htm|archivedate=November 28, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vadim.www.media.mit.edu/Yahoo1.htm|title=Notice of Infringement|accessdate=September 18, 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031222204849/http://vadim.www.media.mit.edu/Yahoo1.htm|archivedate=December 22, 2003}}</ref> He resumed making it available in August 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm|title=Tetris Story|date=August 21, 2006|accessdate=September 18, 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821183909/http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm|archivedate=August 21, 2006}}</ref> Around 2009, TTC and Tetris Holding LLC brought legal action against BioSocia, Inc., on the grounds that BioSocia's \"Blockles\" game infringed on proprietary rights that were held by TTC and Tetris Holding LLC.<ref name=\"blockles_case\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090910006464/en/Resolution-Litigation-%E2%80%9CBlockles%E2%80%9D-Announced-Tetris-Holding-LLC|title=Resolution of Litigation Regarding \"Blockles\" Announced by Tetris Holding, The Tetris Company, BioSocia, Inc. and Charles Forman|publisher=[[BusinessWire]]|date=September 10, 2009|accessdate=February 18, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708105430/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090910006464/en/Resolution-Litigation-%E2%80%9CBlockles%E2%80%9D-Announced-Tetris-Holding-LLC|archive-date=July 8, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 10, 2009, the legal case against BioSocia was resolved, with BioSocia agreeing to discontinue making the \"Blockles\" game available to the public.<ref name=\"blockles_case\"/> In May 2010, TTC's legal counsel sent cease and desist letters to Google insisting that 35 ''Tetris'' clones be removed from the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[Android Market|Market]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2010/06/google-blocks-tetris-clones-from-android-market/ |title=Google blocks Tetris clones from Android market |website=Ars Technica |author=Paul, Ryan |date=June 2, 2010 |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202210616/http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2010/06/google-blocks-tetris-clones-from-android-market/ |archive-date=December 2, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> A US District Court judge ruled in June 2012 that the ''Tetris'' clone \"Mino\" from Xio Interactive infringed on The Tetris Company's copyrights by replicating such elements as the playfield dimensions and the shapes of the blocks.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-06/20/tetris-clone-ruling |title=US judge declares Tetris clone 'infringing' |journal=Wired UK |author=Brown, Mark |date=June 20, 2012 |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623025355/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-06/20/tetris-clone-ruling |archive-date=June 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In addition, it was ruled that Tetris Holding LLC's trade dress had been infringed because \"Mino\" had replicated the form and brightly colored style of the ''Tetris'' Tetriminos and the higher-than-wide rectangular ''Tetris'' playfield.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Attack Of The Clones: Copyright Protection For Video Game Developers |journal=Loyola of Los Angeles Entertainment Law Review |volume=33 Rev 137 |issue=2 (2013) |pages=166\u2013167 |last=Casillas |first=Brian |url=https://digitalcommons.lmu.edu/elr/vol33/iss2/2/ |accessdate=March 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306235034/https://digitalcommons.lmu.edu/elr/vol33/iss2/2/ |archive-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>''\n\n===Newer ''Tetris'' variations===\nIn 2014, in conjunction with the 30th anniversary of the series, Sega released ''[[Puyo Puyo Tetris]]'', a multi-platform game that blends gameplay elements of both the ''Tetris'' and ''[[Puyo Puyo (series)|Puyo Puyo]]'' franchises.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u300c\u3077\u3088\u3077\u3088\u30c6\u30c8\u30ea\u30b9\u300d\u306e\u767a\u58f2\u65e5\u304c2014\u5e742\u67086\u65e5\u306b\u6c7a\u5b9a\u3002\u300c\u30d5\u30a3\u30ae\u30e5\u30a2\u4ed8\u304d3DS/3DS LL\u30ab\u30d0\u30fc\u30bb\u30c3\u30c8\u300d\u3082\u540c\u6642\u767a\u58f2|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/233/G023319/20131028005/|website=4Gamer|accessdate=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221015510/http://www.4gamer.net/games/233/G023319/20131028005/|archive-date=February 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 13, 2019, Nintendo announced and released a new version of the classic game called [[Tetris 99]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SCME2yPJKWk|title=Tetris 99 Announcement in the 2.13.19 Nintendo Direct|last=Nintendo|date=February 13, 2019|website=Youtube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320093729/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SCME2yPJKWk|archive-date=March 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Tetris 99 features a battle royale-style game mode where 99 players play in the same match. In addition to complying with the Tetris Guideline, this version of the game features a unique mechanic known as \"badges.\" Badges lessen the severity of attacks received and amplifies the attacks sent. Players can gain badges by knocking out others who have them. Later in 2019, the 2.0 update introduced \"Invictus\" mode, which is more difficult and competitive than the original version.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/tetris-99-s-2-0-update-includes-a-new-invictus-mode-565827.phtml|title=Tetris 99's 2.0 update includes a new 'Invictus' mode|website=Destructoid|language=english|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> Tetris 99 is only available on the [[Nintendo Switch]].\n\nBased on the success of ''Tetris 99'', the Tetris Company and [[N3TWORK]] are developing ''Tetris Royale'', an [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version of ''Tetris'' that will include a [[battle royale game|battle royale]] mode for 100 players, along with other solo and multiplayer modes. It is expected for release in 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/28/19102611/tetris-royale-mobile-n3twork-nintendo-tetris-99 | title = Tetris Royale, a 100-player battle royale, is coming to mobile devices | first = Dami | last = Lee | date = June 28, 2019 | accessdate = June 28, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190628165710/https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/28/19102611/tetris-royale-mobile-n3twork-nintendo-tetris-99 | archive-date = June 28, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref>{{needsupdate|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Variations ==\n{{more citations needed section|date=June 2012}}\n[[File:Tetris on an iPod.jpg|250px|thumb|A [[iPod classic|5th generation]] [[iPod]] running ''Tetris'' (2006)]]\n\n''Tetris'' has been subject to many changes throughout releases since the release of its first version in 1984. Recent ''Tetris'' games have emphasized pace rather than endurance. Older releases such as Game Boy or NES ''Tetris'' offer records according to points. Since the meter for points is restricted to a specific number of digits, these games' records can be \"maxed out\" by an experienced player. The next big Game Boy release after ''Tetris'', ''Tetris DX'', in marathon mode\u2014comparable to mode A in previous releases\u2014allowed an additional digit for the point meter. Even so, players still maxed it to 9,999,999&nbsp;points after hours of play. For ''[[The New Tetris]]'', world record competitors have spent over 12&nbsp;hours playing the same game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twingalaxies.com/index.aspx?c=12&id=635 |title=Welcome to Twin Galaxies |publisher=Twingalaxies.com |accessdate=November 12, 2008 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080604221115/http://www.twingalaxies.com/index.aspx?c=12&id=635 |archivedate=June 4, 2008 }}</ref> In ''Tetris DX'' and ''The New Tetris'', the new modes sprint and ultra were added. These modes require the player to act under a timer, either to gain the most lines or points in that time. Releases like ''Tetris Worlds'' removed point records. This particular game kept records by how fast a certain number of lines could be cleared depending on the level. Critics of ''Tetris Worlds'' said it was flawed by virtue of the ability of a piece to hover over the bottom for as long as a player needs.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/>\n\nMany different modes of play have been added in recent years. Modes appearing in more than one major release include classic marathon (game A), sprint (otherwise game B or 40 lines), ultra, square, and cascade.\n\nThe field dimension of ''Tetris'' is perhaps the least deviated among releases: almost always 10 cells wide by 20 high. Some releases on handheld platforms with small screens have smaller fields; for example, the ''Tetris Jr.'' [[Handheld electronic game|keychain game]] has 8 by 12, and ''Tetris'' for Game Boy has 10 by 18.\n\nTraditionally, blocks spawn within the four most central columns and the two highest rows. The ''I'' Tetrimino occupies columns 4, 5, 6 and 7, the ''O'' Tetrimino occupies columns 5 and 6, and the remaining 5 Tetriminos occupy columns 4, 5 and 6 (or in some, especially older, versions, 5, 6 and 7). In some more recent games, pieces spawn above the visible playfield.\n\nIn traditional games, a level-up would occur once every ten lines are cleared. In some newer games such as ''Tetris Worlds'', the number of lines required varies upon each new level. After a level-up, points awarded are increased and the blocks fall slightly faster. For example, NES ''Tetris'' operates at 60 frames per second. At level 0, a piece falls one step every 48 frames, and at level 19, a piece falls one step every 2 frames.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} Level increments either terminate at a certain point (Game Boy ''Tetris'' tops off at level 20) or increase forever yet not in speed after a certain point. NES ''Tetris'' will level up in speed until level 29 (due to limitations of the game's engine, pieces are not capable of dropping faster than this), but tool-assisted emulation will show that the level indicator increases indefinitely\u2014eventually leading to a glitch where the meter displays non-numeric characters. Modern games such as ''Tetris the Grand Master'' or ''Tetris Worlds'', at their highest levels, opt to drop a piece more than one row per frame. Pieces will appear to reach the bottom as soon as they spawn. As a result, these games have a delay that lets the player slide the piece on the bottom for a moment to help deal with an otherwise unplayable fall speed. In some games, the hover time is regenerated after a piece is moved or rotated.\n\nSoft drops were first implemented in Nintendo releases of ''Tetris'' so that pieces would be able to drop faster while not locking as to slide into gaps. The other option is hard dropping, which originated in early PC games such as ''Microsoft Tetris'', a game developed by Dave Edson and bundled with [[Microsoft Entertainment Pack]]. With hard dropping, a piece falls and locks in one frame. Newer ''Tetris'' games feature both options. Some games have their locking roles reversed, with soft dropping making the pieces drop faster and locking down, and hard dropping making the pieces drop instantly but not lock.\n\nSingle direction rotation is an older restriction that has since been ruled out in nearly every new official release by the favor of separate buttons for clockwise and one for counter clockwise rotation. In traditional games, the unsymmetrical vertical orientation I-, Z-, and S-pieces will fill the same columns for each clockwise and counter clockwise rotation. Some games vary this by allowing two possible column orientations: one for counter clockwise and one for clockwise rotations. Double rotation\u2014only seen in progressive clones such as ''Quadra'' and ''DTET''\u2014rotates the piece 180\u00b0.\n\nOne of the features most appreciated by skilled players is ''wall kick'' or the ability to rotate the pieces even if these touch the left or right walls. In the NES version, for example, if a Z piece is \"vertically\" aligned and falling touching the left wall, the player cannot rotate the piece, giving the impression that the rotate buttons are locked. In this situation, the player has to move the piece one position to the right before rotating it, losing precious time. Proper implementations of wall kick first appeared in the arcade version of ''Tetris'' by Atari Games.\n\nPiece preview allows a look at the next piece to enter the field. This feature has been implemented since the earliest games, though in those early games, having the preview turned on made the score increase more slowly.\n\n== Variants ==\n{{Main|List of Tetris variants}}\n\nSeveral ''Tetris'' variants exist. Some feature alternate rules and pieces, some feature alternate topologies or dimensions, and others have completely different gameplay.\n\nA popular variant called \"The Grand Master\" eventually becomes so fast players have to use every second of time optimally, and it even has a mode dubbed \"Invisible Tetris\", where the blocks are only shown when falling \u2013 revealed when the game is over.\n\nBecause of its popularity and the relatively simple code required to produce the game, a game with nearly the same rules as ''Tetris'' is often used as a [[Hello world program|hello world]] project for programmers coding for a new system or programming language. This has resulted in the availability of a large number of [[Porting|ports]] for different platforms.\nFor instance, [[\u03bcTorrent]] and [[Emacs|GNU Emacs]] contain similar shape-stacking games as easter eggs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eeggs.com/items/47291.html |title=uTorrent Easter Egg: Tetris in uTorrent |publisher=Eeggs.com |date=March 16, 2006 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121121044523/http://www.eeggs.com/items/47291.html |archive-date=November 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=poenn |url=http://hints.macworld.com/article.php?story=20050103201954271 |title=macosxhints.com \u2013 Play Tetris in Terminal via emacs |publisher=Hints.macworld.com |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522153944/http://hints.macworld.com/article.php?story=20050103201954271 |archive-date=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== End of play ==\nPlayers lose a typical game of ''Tetris'' when they can no longer keep up with the increasing speed, or when the player can not find a timely solution to the Tetriminos they've been given and the Tetriminos stack up to the top of the playing field. This is commonly referred to as \"topping out\".\n\n=== Infinite gameplay impossibility ===\nThe question ''Would it be possible to play forever?'' was first considered in a thesis by John Brzustowski in 1992.<ref>John Brzustowski. [https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/3263/ubc_1992_spring_brzustowski_john.pdf?sequence=1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016151137/https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/3263/ubc_1992_spring_brzustowski_john.pdf?sequence=1 |date=October 16, 2013 }}. Retrieved October 16, 2013.</ref> The conclusion reached was that the game is statistically doomed to end. The reason has to do with the S and Z Tetriminos. If a player receives a sufficiently large sequence of alternating S and Z Tetriminos, the na\u00efve gravity used by the standard game eventually forces the player to leave holes on the board. The holes will necessarily stack to the top and, ultimately, end the game. If the pieces are distributed randomly, this sequence will eventually occur. Thus, if a game with, for example, an ideal, uniform, uncorrelated [[Random number generation|random number generator]] is played long enough, any player will top out.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061209110731/http://www.math.uic.edu/~burgiel/Tetris/explanation.html Dr. Burgiel's Tetris Research Page, Explanation]. Retrieved February 25, 2007.</ref><ref>Heidi Burgiel. [http://www.geom.umn.edu/%7Eburgiel/Tetris/tetris.PS How to Lose at Tetris] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030513033006/http://www.geom.umn.edu/~burgiel/Tetris/tetris.PS |date=May 13, 2003 }}, Mathematical Gazette, vol. 81, pp. 194\u2013200 1997</ref>\n\nIn practice, this does not occur in most ''Tetris'' variants. Some [[List of Tetris variants|variants]] allow the player to choose to play with only S and Z Tetriminos, and a good player may survive well over 150 consecutive Tetriminos this way. On an implementation with an ideal uniform randomizer, the probability at any given time of the next 150 Tetriminos being only S and Z is ({{sfrac|2|7}})<sup>150</sup> (approximately {{val|2e-82}}). Most implementations use a [[pseudorandom number generator]] to generate the sequence of Tetriminos, and such an S\u2013Z sequence is almost certainly not contained in the sequence produced by the 32-bit [[linear congruential generator]] in many implementations (which has roughly {{val|4.2e9}} states). The \"evil\" algorithm in ''Bastet'' (an unofficial variant) often starts a game with a series of more than seven Z pieces.\n\nModern versions of ''Tetris'' released after 2001 use a bag-style randomizer that guarantees players will never receive more than four S or Z pieces in a row. This is one of the \"Indispensable Rules\" enforced by the ''Tetris Guideline'' that all officially licensed ''Tetris'' games must follow.<ref name=\"tftt\"/>\n\nRecent versions of ''Tetris'' such as ''Tetris Worlds'' allow the player to repeatedly rotate a block once it hits the bottom of the playfield without it locking into place (see [[#Easy spin dispute|Easy spin dispute]], above). This permits a player to play for an infinite amount of time, though not necessarily to land an infinite number of blocks.\n\n== Computational complexity ==\nIn [[computer science]], it is common to analyze the [[Computational complexity theory|computational complexity]] of problems, including real life problems and games. It was proven that for the \"offline\" version of ''Tetris'' (the player knows the complete sequence of pieces that will be dropped, i.e. there is no hidden information) the following objectives are [[NP-complete]]:\n* Maximizing the number of rows cleared while playing the given piece sequence.\n* Maximizing the number of pieces placed before a loss occurs.\n* Maximizing the number of simultaneous clearing of four rows.\n* Minimizing the height of the highest filled grid square over the course of the sequence.\n\nAlso, it is [[Hardness of approximation|difficult to even approximately solve]] the first, second, and fourth problem.  It is [[NP-hard]], given an initial gameboard and a sequence of ''p'' pieces, to approximate the first two problems to within a factor of {{nowrap|''p''<sup>1 \u2212 ''\u03b5''</sup>}} for any constant {{nowrap|''\u03b5'' > 0}}.\nIt is NP-hard to approximate the last problem within a factor of {{nowrap|2 \u2212 ''\u03b5''}} for any constant {{nowrap|''\u03b5'' > 0}}.\n\nTo prove NP-completeness, it was shown that there is a polynomial [[Reduction (complexity)|reduction]] between the [[3-partition problem]], which is also NP-complete, and the ''Tetris'' problem.<ref>{{cite conference|url=http://erikdemaine.org/papers/Tetris_COCOON2003/paper.pdf|title=Tetris is Hard, Even to Approximate|last1=Demaine|first1=Erik D.|last2=Hohenberger|first2=Susan|last3=Liben-Nowell|first3=David|date=July 25\u201328, 2003|conference=Proceedings of the 9th International Computing and Combinatorics Conference (COCOON 2003)|conferenceurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105042734/http://www.cs.montana.edu/bhz/cocoon03.html|location=Big Sky, Montana|access-date=December 18, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613201613/http://erikdemaine.org/papers/Tetris_COCOON2003/paper.pdf|archive-date=June 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{See also|Korobeiniki#Tetris arrangements and modern cover versions|Tetris (Game Boy video game)#Music}}\n\n=== Game Boy version ===\n* Music A has become a well-known song in its own right. It is an instrumental arrangement of a Russian folk tune called \"[[Korobeiniki]]\", which has been covered by UK dance band [[Doctor Spin]], US alternative rock band [[Ozma (band)|Ozma]], [[Tokyo Ska Paradise Orchestra]], [[Basshunter]], Doctor P, and the German [[techno]] group [[Scooter (band)|Scooter]] on their 2007 album ''[[Jumping All Over the World]]''. It was also sampled in \"21 Concepts\" by [[MC Lars]]. Music A and B are also remixed and arranged for ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'', and can be selected for the stage ''[[Luigi's Mansion]]'', as well as being used in custom stages. The remixes were brought back in [[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U|''Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS'' and ''Wii U'']], Music A playing in ''Luigi's Mansion'' and custom stages in the Wii U version and being one of the bonus songs to play in the 3DS exclusive \"Smash Run\" mode, and Music B playing in \"Wuhu Island\" from ''[[Wii Sports Resort]]'' and in custom stages, Music A and B yet again were brought back for ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'' and can be played on the stages \"Summit\" from ''[[Ice Climber]]'', \"Hanenbow\" from ''[[Electroplankton]]'', ''[[Balloon Fight]]'', \"Living Room\" from ''[[Nintendogs]]'', ''[[Find Mii]]'', ''[[Tomodachi Life]]'', ''[[PictoChat]] 2'', ''[[Duck Hunt]]'', ''[[Wrecking Crew (video game)|Wrecking Crew]]'', ''[[Pilotwings]]'', Wuhu Island and custom stages. The song has also been remixed for two dance games, under the name \"Pumptris Quattro\" in ''[[Pump It Up NX2]]'' and \"Happy-hopper\" in ''[[Dance Maniax]] 2nd Mix''. [[Ronan Murray]] has recorded an arrangement of the tune for [[pipe organ]]. The A theme was adapted by Australian musical group [[Flap!]], with original lyrics added, on their debut album ''Flap!''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/artist/flap!/id410490346 |title=iTunes - Music - Flap! |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |accessdate=July 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218023052/https://itunes.apple.com/au/artist/flap!/id410490346 |archive-date=December 18, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Music B is an original track by [[Hirokazu Tanaka]], the game's sound designer. \n* Music C is an arrangement of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s [[French Suites, BWV 812-817|French Suite No. 3 In B Minor, BWV 814, IV. Menuett \u2013 Trio]].\n\n=== Nintendo Entertainment System version ===\n* Music 1 in Nintendo's NES version is \"Dance of the Sugar Plum Fairy\", a tune noted to be scene 14c of act two of ''[[The Nutcracker]]'', composed by [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]].\n* One song in the [[Blue Planet Software|BPS]] and [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]] versions is the [[Kalinka (song)|\"Kalinka\"]] (or Karinka, as referred in-game), a famous Russian song written by [[Ivan Larionov|Ivan Petrovich Larionov]].\n* The victory song playing while the rocket blasts off is George's Bizet's \"Les Toreadors\" from ''Carmen'' Suite No. 1.\n\n=== Atari version ===\nAtari's arcade version of ''Tetris'', and its NES port by subsidiary Tengen have original pieces composed by Brad Fuller, as well as traditional Russian tunes also arranged by Fuller.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vgmpf.com/Wiki/index.php?title=Tetris:_Tengen_%28NES%29 |title=Tetris: Tengen (NES) - Videogame Music Preservation Foundation Wiki |publisher=Vgmpf.com |date=August 15, 2013 |accessdate=July 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316201250/http://www.vgmpf.com/Wiki/index.php?title=Tetris:_Tengen_%28NES%29 |archive-date=March 16, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Cognitive effects ==\n{{See also|Tetris effect}}\nAccording to research from Dr. Richard Haier, ''et al.'' prolonged ''Tetris'' activity can also lead to more efficient brain activity during play.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Richard J Haier|author2=Sherif Karama|author3=Leonard Leyba|author4=Rex E Jung|title=MRI assessment of cortical thickness and functional activity changes in adolescent girls following three months of practice on a visual-spatial task|journal=BMC Research Notes|year=2009|doi=10.1186/1756-0500-2-174|pmid=19723307|volume=2|page=174|pmc=2746806}}</ref> When first playing ''Tetris'', brain function and activity increases, along with greater cerebral energy consumption, measured by [[glucose]] metabolic rate. As ''Tetris'' players become more proficient, their brains show a reduced consumption of glucose, indicating more efficient brain activity for this task.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Haier RJ, Siegel BV, MacLachlan A, Soderling E, Lottenberg S, Buchsbaum MS|title=Regional glucose metabolic changes after learning a complex visuospatial/motor task: a positron emission tomographic study|journal=Brain Res.|volume=570|issue=1\u20132|pages=134\u201343|date=January 1992|pmid=1617405|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(92)90573-R}}</ref> Moderate play of ''Tetris'' (half-an-hour a day for three months) boosts general cognitive functions such as \"critical thinking, reasoning, language and processing\" and increases [[cerebral cortex]] thickness.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/6122290/Tetris-could-boost-brain-power.html Tetris 'could boost brain power'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212121948/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/6122290/Tetris-could-boost-brain-power.html |date=February 12, 2010 }} Telegraph news, September 2, 2009</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, an Oxford University research group headed by Dr. Emily Holmes reported in ''[[PLoS ONE]]'' that for healthy volunteers, playing ''Tetris'' soon after viewing traumatic material in the laboratory reduced the number of flashbacks to those scenes in the following week. They believe that the computer game may disrupt the memories that are retained of the sights and sounds witnessed at the time, and which are later re-experienced through involuntary, distressing flashbacks of that moment. The group hopes to develop this approach further as a potential intervention to reduce the flashbacks experienced in [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] but emphasized that these are only preliminary results.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Holmes EA|author2=James EL|author3=Coode-Bate T|author4=Deeprose C|title=Can playing the computer game \"Tetris\" reduce the build-up of flashbacks for trauma? A proposal from cognitive science|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=4|issue=1|pages= e4153|year=2009|pmid=19127289|pmc=2607539|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0004153|editor1-last=Bell|editor1-first=Vaughan|bibcode=2009PLoSO...4.4153H}}</ref>\n\nProfessor Jackie Andrade and Jon May, from [[Plymouth University]]'s Cognition Institute, and Ph.D. student Jessica Skorka-Brown have conducted research that shows that playing ''Tetris'' could distract from cravings and give a \"quick and manageable\" fix for people struggling to stick to diets, or quit smoking or drinking.<ref>{{cite news|last=GANDER|first=KASHMIRA|title=Playing Tetris could help with weight loss and smokers' cravings, psychologists claim|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/playing-tetris-could-help-with-weight-loss-and-smokers-cravings-psychologists-claim-9149045.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=February 24, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224123004/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/playing-tetris-could-help-with-weight-loss-and-smokers-cravings-psychologists-claim-9149045.html|archive-date=February 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnother notable effect is that, according to a Canadian study in April 2013, playing ''Tetris'' has been found to treat older adolescents with [[amblyopia]] (lazy eye), which was better than patching a victim's well eye to train their weaker eye. Dr. Robert Hess of the research team said: \"It's much better than patching \u2013 much more enjoyable; it's faster, and it seems to work better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/04/23/study-finds-tetris-effectively-treats-lazy-eye|title=A Study Find That ''Tetris'' Effectively Treats a Lazy Eye|author=Luke Karmali|website=[[IGN]]|date=April 23, 2013|accessdate=June 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620113327/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/04/23/study-finds-tetris-effectively-treats-lazy-eye|archive-date=June 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Tested in the [[United Kingdom]], this experiment also appears to help children with that problem.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-17616818|title=Video Game Treatment for a Lazy Eye|work=[[BBC News]]|date=April 4, 2012|accessdate=June 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819214014/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-17616818|archive-date=August 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game has been noted to cause the brain to involuntarily picture ''Tetris'' combinations even when the player is not playing (the [[Tetris effect|''Tetris'' effect]]), although this can occur with any computer game or situation showcasing repeated images or scenarios, such as a [[jigsaw puzzle]]. While debates about Tetris's cognitive benefits continue, at least some researchers view it as a milestone in the gamification of education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.elearninginside.com/game-changing-arrival-tetris-united-states/|title=It has been 30 years since Tetris arrived in the U.S.|date=January 29, 2018|work=eLearningInside News|access-date=November 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116085344/https://news.elearninginside.com/game-changing-arrival-tetris-united-states/|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Hasbro Games ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2018}}\nIn 2013, The Tetris Company signed a contract with Hasbro to make a [[Bop It]] and a [[Jenga]] themed version of ''Tetris''. The games were shown at the New York Toy Fair and Bop It Tetris was sold on Amazon.com in June 2013.\n\nJenga Tetris is like Jenga but using ''Tetris'' shapes.\n\nBop It Tetris is an [[audio game]]. It has several game modes including ''Marathon'' and ''Pass It''. In the Marathon Mode, the player has four lives and has to complete the puzzles with the square lights. The game unit has three actions which are: \"Slam It\" which slams the top part of the device down, \"Slide it\", a screen which can rotate from left and right, and \"Spin It\", where the device can spin. If the player fails to complete the puzzle, the voice of Buddy Rubino will make a [[Santa Claus]] type laugh and will encourage the player with a comment such as: \"Squares man! They're just squares!\" or \"Shapes are hard!\" and Buddy will then say \"Life lost\" and one of the four squares on the top screen will disappear. After every stage is completed Buddy will tell the player with a comment such as: \"Level up!\" and there will then be a 45-second bonus round which the player can score two or more bonus points.\n\nIn the Pass It Mode, it is the same as the Marathon mode except Buddy Rubino will say \"Pass It\" to let other people join in.\n\n== Reception and Legacy==\n{{Video game reviews\n| Allgame = Arcade: {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Cook|first=Brad|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2784&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114201703/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2784&tab=review|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 14, 2014|publisher=AllGame|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />C64: {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Sutyak|first=Jonathan|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16887&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004356/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16887&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />Macintosh: {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Savignano|first=Lisa Karen|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11800&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004358/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11800&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame|url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />NES&nbsp;(Tengen):&nbsp;{{Rating|4.5|5}}&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Skyler|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14911&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004353/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14911&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />NES&nbsp;(Nintendo):&nbsp;{{Rating|4.5|5}}&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web|last=Weiss|first=Brett Alan|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=1331&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216081022/http://allgame.com/game.php?id=1331&tab=review|archive-date=February 16, 2010|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| CVG = 94%<ref name=\"CVG-1989-review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4f2e51c9cdbbfbe/800/800 |title=Tetris Mastertronic |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |issue=92 |page=74 |date=June 1989 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032455/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4f2e51c9cdbbfbe/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| CRASH = 77%<ref name=\"Crash-19880review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/78d7602b35d0e2d/800/800 |title=Reviews: Tetris |magazine=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]] |issue=50 |page=10 |date=March 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032452/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/78d7602b35d0e2d/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| SUser = {{Rating|10|10}}<ref name=\"SinclairU-1988-review\">{{cite web |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/c53e67fb08dbe15/800/800 |title=TET\u042fIS: Arcade Review |magazine=[[Sinclair User]] |issue=1988 |page=13 |date=February 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032457/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/c53e67fb08dbe15/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| YSinclair = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Worrall|first=Tony|title=Tetris|url=http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/tetris.htm|publisher=The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years|accessdate=August 8, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427113515/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/tetris.htm|archivedate=April 27, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Zzap!64]]''\n| rev1Score = 98%<ref>{{cite web|title=Gold Standard|url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/zzap100/100thspec5.html|publisher=The Def Gui to Zzap!64|accessdate=August 8, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Dzo6NOv6?url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/zzap100/100thspec5.html|archive-date=January 28, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]]''\n| rev2Score = 95%<ref name=\"ACE-1988-review\">{{cite web |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4852d3d00d9894b/800/800 |title=Tetris: Can MIRRORSOFT pack them in? |publisher=[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]] |issue=5 |page=49 |date=February 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417035859/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4852d3d00d9894b/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| award1Pub = Zzap!64\n| award1 = Gold Medal\n| award2Pub = Sinclair User\n| award2 = SU Classic\n}}\n''[[Compute!]]'' called the IBM version of ''Tetris'' \"one of the most addictive computer games this side of the [[Berlin Wall]] ... [it] is ''not'' the game to start if you have work to do or an appointment to keep. Consider yourself warned\".<ref name=\"weatherman198807\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_098_1988_Jul#page/n73/mode/2up | title=Tetris | work=Compute! | date=July 1988 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | author=Weatherman, Lynne | page=72 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211621/https://archive.org/stream/1988-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_098_1988_Jul#page/n73/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[Orson Scott Card]] joked that the game \"proves that Russia still wants to [[We will bury you|bury us]]. I shudder to think of the blow to our economy as computer productivity drops to 0\". Noting that ''Tetris'' was not copy-protected, he wrote \"Obviously, the game is meant to find its way onto every American machine\".<ref name=\"card198904\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_107_1989_Apr#page/n11/mode/2up | title=Gameplay | work=Compute! | date=April 1989 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | author=Card, Orson Scott | page=11 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211723/https://archive.org/stream/1989-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_107_1989_Apr#page/n11/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The IBM version of the game was reviewed in 1988 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' No. 135 by Hartley, Patricia, and Kirk Lesser in \"The Role of Computers\" column. The reviewers gave the game 4.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Dragon135\">{{cite journal|title=The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|last2=Lesser|last3=Lesser|first1=Hartley|first2=Patricia|first3=Kirk|journal=Dragon|issue=135|date=July 1988|pages=82\u201389}}</ref> The Lessers later reviewed Spectrum HoloByte's [[Macintosh]] version of ''Tetris'' in 1989 in ''Dragon'' No. 141, giving that version 5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Dragon141\">{{cite journal|title= The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|last2=Lesser|last3=Lesser|first1=Hartley|first2=Patricia|first3=Kirk|journal=Dragon|issue=141|date= January 1989|pages=72\u201378}}</ref> ''[[Macworld]]'' reviewed the Macintosh version of ''Tetris'' in 1988, praising its stategic gameplay, stating that \"''Tetris'' offers the rare combination of being simple to learn but extremely challenging to play\", and also praising the inclusion of the [[Desk Accessory]] version, which uses less RAM. ''Macworld'' summarized their review by listing ''Tetris' ''pros and cons, stating that ''Tetris'' is \"Elegant; easy to play; challenging and addicting; requires quick thinking, long-term strategy, and lightning reflexes\" and listed ''Tetris''' cons as \"None.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last = Buderi|first = Robert|title = Tetris 1.0 Review|date = December 1988|url = https://archive.org/details/MacWorld_8812_December_1988/page/n181|magazine = Macworld|publisher = Mac Publishing|page = 178}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the ZX Spectrum version of the game was voted number 49 in the ''[[Your Sinclair]] Official Top 100 Games of All Time''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Top 100 Games of All Time|journal=Your Sinclair|date=September 1993}}</ref> In 1996, ''Tetris Pro'' was ranked the 38th best game of all time by ''[[Amiga Power]]''.<ref>Amiga Power magazine issue 64, Future Publishing, August 1996</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' picked the game as the #8 greatest game available in 1991, saying: \"Thanks to Nintendo\u2019s endless promotion, Tetris has become one of the most popular video games.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://ew.com/article/1991/11/22/video-games-guide/ | title=Video Games Guide | access-date=September 9, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219184932/http://ew.com/article/1991/11/22/video-games-guide/ | archive-date=February 19, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Computer Gaming World'' gave ''Tetris'' the 1989 Compute! Choice Award for Arcade Game, describing it as \"by far, the most addictive game ever\".<ref name=\"compute198901\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | title=The 189 Compute! Choice Awards | work=Compute! | date=January 1989 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | page=24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316200847/https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The game won three [[Software Publishers Association]] Excellence in Software Awards in 1989, including Best Entertainment Program and the Critic's Choice Award for consumers.<ref name=\"scisco198908\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_111_1989_Aug#page/n7/mode/2up | title=the Envelope, Please | work=Compute! | date=August 1989 | accessdate=November 11, 2013 | author=Scisco, Peter | page=6 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211940/https://archive.org/stream/1989-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_111_1989_Aug#page/n7/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Computer Gaming World'' in 1996 ranked it 14th on the magazine's list of the most innovative computer games.<ref name=\"cgw199611mostinnovative\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=The 15 Most Innovative Computer Games | work=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | accessdate=March 25, 2016 | pages=102 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408023915/http://cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | archive-date=April 8, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> That same year, ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' listed it as number 2 on their \"Top 100 Games of All Time\", commenting that, \"There is something so perfect, so [[Zen]] about the falling blocks of ''Tetris'' that the game has captured the interest of everyone who has ever played it.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Top 100 Games of All Time |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|page=71}}</ref> On March 12, 2007, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that ''Tetris'' was named to a list of the ten most important video games of all time, the so-called [[game canon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/12/arts/design/12vide.html?ex=1331352000&en=380fc9bb18694da5&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|title=Is That Just Some Game? No, It's a Cultural Artifact|newspaper=[[nytimes.com]]|first=HEATHER|last=CHAPLIN|date=March 12, 2007|accessdate=November 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204212137/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/12/arts/design/12vide.html?ex=1331352000&en=380fc9bb18694da5&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|archive-date=December 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> After announced at the 2007 [[Game Developers Conference]], the [[Library of Congress]] took up the video game preservation proposal and began with these 10 games, including ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"Joystiq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2007/03/12/10-most-important-video-games-of-all-time-as-judged-by-2-design/ |title=10 most important video games of all time, as judged by 2 designers, 2 academics, and 1 lowly blogger |last=Ransom-Wiley |first=James |publisher=Joystiq |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422035847/http://www.joystiq.com/2007/03/12/10-most-important-video-games-of-all-time-as-judged-by-2-design/ |archivedate=April 22, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/09/yes-the-library-of-congress-has-video-games-an-interview-with-david-gibson/ |title=Yes, The Library of Congress Has Video Games: An Interview with David Gibson |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=January 18, 2013 |publisher=blogs.loc.gov |first=Trevor |last=Owens |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205100245/http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/09/yes-the-library-of-congress-has-video-games-an-interview-with-david-gibson/ |archivedate=December 5, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, video game website [[GameFAQs]] hosted its sixth annual \"[[GameFAQs#Contests|Character Battle]]\", in which the users nominate their favorite video game characters for a popularity contest in which characters participate. The L-shaped ''Tetris'' piece (or \"L-Block\" as it was called) entered the contest as a joke character, but on November 4, 2007, it won the contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/cb6|title=Fall 2007: The Great GameFAQs Character Battle VI|website=GameFAQs|accessdate=November 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029201304/http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/cb6|archive-date=October 29, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 6, 2009, Google honored ''Tetris''{{'}} 25-year anniversary by changing its logotype to a version drawn with ''Tetris'' blocks \u2013 the \"l\" letter being the long ''Tetris'' block lowering into its place,<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Features TETRIS Look For Game's 25th Anniversary|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090605005609/en|publisher=Electronic Arts|date=June 5, 2009|quote=Google will roll out the TETRIS-inspired design in 24-hour periods, starting first at 1:00&nbsp;pm EDT in Japan, Australia, and New Zealand. From 6:00&nbsp;pm&nbsp; \u2013 7:00&nbsp;pm EDT, the TETRIS-inspired design will begin appearing in Europe, Asia, Africa, and the Middle East. Starting June 6th, at 12:00&nbsp;am EDT, the TETRIS-inspired design will be available in North and South America.|accessdate=September 25, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110216141150/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090605005609/en|archive-date=February 16, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> seen here.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/25-years-of-tetris-courtesy-of-tetris-holding-llc |title=25 Years of Tetris \u2013 courtesy of Tetris Holding, LLC |date=June 6, 2009 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104165253/http://www.google.com/doodles/25-years-of-tetris-courtesy-of-tetris-holding-llc |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, ''[[Game Informer]]'' put ''Tetris'' 3rd on their list of \"The Top 200 Games of All Time\", saying that \"If a game could be considered ageless, it's ''Tetris''\".<ref name=\"gi_best\">{{cite journal|author=The ''Game Informer'' staff|title=The Top 200 Games of All Time|pages=44\u201379|issue= 200|date=December 2009|journal=Game Informer|issn=1067-6392|oclc=27315596}}</ref> The ''Game Informer'' staff also placed it third on their 2001 list of the 100 best games ever.<ref>{{cite web |title=Game Informer's Top 100 Games of All Time (Circa Issue 100) |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx |work=[[Game Informer]] |last=Cork |first=Jeff |date=November 16, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100408113757/http://gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx |archive-date=April 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''{{'}}s 100th issue had ''Tetris'' as first place in the \"100 Best Games of All Time\", commenting that \"''Tetris'' is as pure as a video game can get. ... When the right blocks come your way - and if you can manage to avoid mistakes - the game can be relaxing. One mislaid block, however, and your duties switch to damage control, a mad, panicky dash to clean up your mess or die.\" ''Tetris'' was also the only game for which the list did not specify one or two versions; the editors explained that after deadlocking over which version was best, they concluded that there was no wrong version of ''Tetris'' to play.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=100 Best Games of All Time |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=100 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=November 1997|page=160}} Note: Contrary to the title, the intro to the article (on page 100) explicitly states that the list covers console video games only, meaning PC games and arcade games were not eligible.</ref> In 2007, ''Tetris'' came in second place in [[IGN]]'s \"100 Greatest Video Games of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_2.html |title=IGN Top 100 Games of All Time \u2013 2007 |publisher=Top100.ign.com |date= |accessdate=November 22, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107133844/http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_2.html|archivedate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> In January 2010, it was announced that the [[List of Tetris variants|''Tetris'' franchise]] had sold more than 170 million copies, approximately 70 million physical copies and over 100 million copies [[Tetris (Electronic Arts)|for cell phones]],<ref name=guardian020609>''[[The Guardian]]'', June 2, 2009, [https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov How Tetris conquered the world, block by block] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329135242/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov |date=March 29, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maximejohnson.com/techno/2010/01/tetris-atteint-les-100-millions-de-telechargements-payants-et-une-petite-histoire-du-jeu/ |title=\u00bb Tetris atteint les 100 millions de t\u00e9l\u00e9chargements payants (et une petite histoire du jeu) \u2013 Maximejohnson.com/techno : actualit\u00e9s technologiques, tests et opinions par le j |publisher=Maximejohnson.com |date=January 19, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726141129/http://www.maximejohnson.com/techno/2010/01/tetris-atteint-les-100-millions-de-telechargements-payants-et-une-petite-histoire-du-jeu/ |archive-date=July 26, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> making it one of the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchises of all time]]. {{As of|2011|12}}, ''Tetris'' has sold 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads.<ref>{{cite news |title=EA Launches New Tetris\u00ae Game on the App Store Today |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111201006159/en/EA-Launches-New-Tetris%C2%AE-Game-App-Store |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, ''[[PC Format]]'' named ''Tetris'' one of the 50 best computer games ever. The editors called it \"incredibly addictive\" and \"one of the best games of all time\".<ref name=pcformat50>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[PC Format]] | title=The 50 best games EVER! |date=October 1991 | issue=1 | pages=109\u2013111 }}</ref>\n\n''[[Guinness World Records]]'' has recognized the game as being the most ported in the history of video gaming, appearing on in excess of 65 different platforms by 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/most-ported-computer-game/ |title=Most ported computer game |publisher=Guinnessworldrecords.com |date=October 1, 2010 |accessdate=June 7, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223258/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/most-ported-computer-game/ |archive-date=December 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThere was a hoax that circulated in February 2019 that the original NES instruction manual for ''Tetris'' had named the seven tetrominos with names like \"Orange Ricky\", \"Hero\" and \"Smashboy\", but was disproven. Despite being disproven by video game historians, a question on the October 7, 2019 airing of ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' alluded to these names.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/jeopardy-airs-a-hilariously-incorrect-bit-of-tetris-tr-1838889592 | title = Jeopardy! Airs A Hilariously Incorrect Bit Of Tetris Trivia | first = Chris | last = Kohler | date = October 8, 2019 | accessdate = October 8, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\n=== In research ===\n''Tetris'' has been the subject of academic research. [[Vladimir Pokhilko]] was the first clinical psychologist to conduct experiments using ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"MarkWolf2012\">{{cite book | author=Mark J. P. Wolf | title=Encyclopedia of Video Games: The Culture, Technology, and Art of Gaming | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=deBFx7QAwsQC&pg=PA642 | accessdate=February 5, 2013 | date=August 31, 2012 | publisher=ABC-CLIO | isbn=978-0-313-37936-9 | page=642 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528022924/http://books.google.com/books?id=deBFx7QAwsQC&pg=PA642 | archive-date=May 28, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, it has been used for research in several fields including the [[theory of computation]], algorithmic theory, and [[cognitive psychology]].\n\nDuring the game of ''Tetris'', blocks appear to [[Adsorption|adsorb]] onto the lower surface of the window. This has led scientists to use tetrominoes \"as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape\" to model their \"[[adsorption]] on a flat surface\" to study the [[thermodynamics]] of [[nanoparticles]].<ref>[https://arstechnica.com/science/news/2009/05/the-thermodynamics-of-tetris.ars The Thermodynamics of Tetiris] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912220000/http://arstechnica.com/science/news/2009/05/the-thermodynamics-of-tetris.ars |date=September 12, 2011 }}, Ars Technica, 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1021/la900196b| pmid=19397254|title = Structure, Thermodynamics, and Solubility in Tetromino Fluids| journal=Langmuir| volume=25| issue=12| pages=6702\u20136716|year = 2009|last1 = Barnes|first1 = Brian C.| last2=Siderius| first2=Daniel W.| last3=Gelb| first3=Lev D.}}</ref>\n\n== Film ==\n[[Threshold Entertainment]] has teamed up with The Tetris Company to develop a film adaptation of ''Tetris''. Threshold's CEO describes the film as an epic sci-fi adventure that will form part of a trilogy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/tetris-movie-story|title='Tetris' Movie Planned as an Epic Sci-Fi Adventure|work=Movieweb|date=September 30, 2014|accessdate=September 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001011505/http://www.movieweb.com/tetris-movie-story|archive-date=October 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tetris-movie-be-80m-us-894779|title='Tetris' Movie to Be $80M U.S.-China Co-Production|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Brzeski|first=Patrick|date=May 17, 2016|access-date=May 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518095550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tetris-movie-be-80m-us-894779|archive-date=May 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, sources reported on a press release claiming the film would be shot in China in 2017 with an $80 million budget. However, no 2017 or later sources confirm the film ever actually went into production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2016/05/17/tetris-movie-real/|title=Is this 'Tetris' movie for real? Too many key blocks are missing to be sure|last=Dickey|first=Josh|date=May 17, 2016|publisher=Mashable|access-date=June 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624093105/https://mashable.com/2016/05/17/tetris-movie-real/|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Tetris'' appeared in the 2010 short animated film [[Pixels (2010 film)|''Pixels'']], and in the 2015 movie ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'' inspired by the former.<ref>{{Citation|title=Pixels (2015)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2120120/movieconnections|accessdate=February 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118041924/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2120120/movieconnections|archive-date=November 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Video Games|1980s|1990s}}\n* ''[[Pentomino]]'' [[tiling puzzle]]s and games are popular in [[recreational mathematics]].\n* ''[[Brain Wall]]'' and ''[[Blokken]]'' \u2014 game shows based on ''Tetris''\n* ''[[Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters]]'' \u2014 2011 documentary about the 2010 ''Tetris'' Championships featuring interviews with Pajitnov and Dr. Richard Haier.\n* ''[[Game Over (book)|Game Over]]'' \u2014 1993 book covering Nintendo history, including interviews with Alexey Pajitnov and others regarding ''Tetris'' licensing.\n* [[List of Tetris variants|List of ''Tetris'' variants]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web | url = http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm | title = Tetris Story | last = Gerasimov | first = Vadim | website = [[Vadim Gerasimov|OverSigma]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/mathematicians-prove-tetr/ | title = Mathematicians Prove Tetris Is Tough | last = Graham | first = Sarah | date = October 29, 2002 | website = [[Scientific American]]}}\n* {{cite AV media | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00mdqf8 | title = The creation of Tetris | date = December 29, 2012 | website = [[BBC World Service]] | publisher = [[BBC]]}}\n* {{IMDb title|0409371|Tetris: From Russia with Love}}\n* {{IMDb title|1836974|Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Books===\n* {{Cite book |last1=Loguidice |first1=Bill |last2=Barton |first2=Matt |year=2009 |title=Vintage Games: An Insider Look at the History of the Most Influential Games of All Time |url=https://www.routledge.com/Vintage-Games-An-Insider-Look-at-the-History-of-Grand-Theft-Auto-Super/Loguidice-Barton/p/book/9780240811468 |edition=1st |publisher=[[Focal Press]] |pages=291\u2013301 |isbn=0240811461}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Kent |first=Steven |title=The Ultimate History of Video Games: From Pong to Pokemon: The Story Behind the Craze That Touched Our Lives and Changed the World |publisher=Three Rivers Press |year=2001 |edition=1st |pages=377-381 |isbn=9780761536437}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Sheff |first1=David |last2=Eddy |first2=Andy |title=Game Over: Press Start to Continue |publisher=Cyberactive Media Group |year=1999 |edition=1st |pages=295-348 |isbn=0966961706}} \n* {{Cite book |last=Trefry |first=Gregory |title=Casual Game Design: Designing Play for the Gamer in All of Us |publisher=CRC Press |year=2010 |pages=179-185 |isbn=0123749530 |url=https://www.crcpress.com/Casual-Game-Design-Designing-Play-for-the-Gamer-in-ALL-of-Us/Trefry/p/book/9780123749536}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Brzustowski |first=John |title=Can You Win at Tetris? |year=1992 |publisher=University of British Columbia |url=https://open.library.ubc.ca/cIRcle/collections/ubctheses/831/items/1.0079748}}\n\n===Instruction manuals===\n* {{Cite book |title=Tetris (Game Boy) Instruction Booklet |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |year=1989 |url=http://www.superluigibros.com/downloads/manuals/gameboy/Tetris_-_Manual_-_GB.pdf}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Tetris 2 Instruction Booklet |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |year=1993 |url=http://www.nesfiles.com/NES/Tetris_2/Tetris_2.pdf}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Tetris DS Instruction booklet |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |year=2006 |url=http://www.nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/DS_Tetris_DS.pdf}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|collapsible=collapsed}}\n* {{Official website|https://tetris.com}}\n* {{IAg|tetris_1987|Tetris|MS-DOS}}\n\n{{Template group\n|title = Articles related to the game of ''Tetris''\n|titlestyle = background:#e8ddff\n|list  =\n{{Tetris|state=expanded}}\n{{Polyforms|state=expanded}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Tetris| ]]\n[[Category:1984 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:1984 video games]]\n[[Category:Alexey Pajitnov games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Falling block puzzle games]]\n[[Category:NP-complete problems]]\n[[Category:Russian inventions]]\n[[Category:Soviet brands]]\n[[Category:Soviet games]]\n[[Category:Soviet inventions]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1984 video game}}\n{{short description|tile-matching puzzle video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Tetris\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = AcademySoft\n| publisher = AcademySoft\n| designer = [[Alexey Pajitnov]]\n| platforms = [[Electronika 60]], [[IBM PC]], [[MS-DOS]], Others {{small|(see [[List of Tetris variants]] for other versions)}}\n| released = '''Electronika 60'''{{Video game release|[[Soviet Union|USSR]]|June 6, 1984}}'''MS-DOS''' & '''IBM PC'''{{Video game release|USSR|1986}}\n| genre = [[Puzzle video game|Puzzle]], [[Tile-matching video game|Tile-matching]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Tetris''''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0422\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0441}} {{IPA-ru|\u02c8t\u025btr\u02b2\u026as|}}; [[portmanteau]] of \"[[tetromino]]\" and \"[[tennis]]\") is a [[Tile-matching video game|tile-matching]] [[puzzle video game]] originally designed and programmed by Soviet Russian software engineer [[Alexey Pajitnov]].<ref name=\"tri\">{{Triangulation|273|Dan Ackerman}}</ref> The first playable version was completed on June 6, 1984,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/02/us-videogames-tetris-idUSTRE5510V020090602|work=Reuters|title=At 25, Tetris still eyeing growth|date=June 2, 2009|access-date=July 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106192245/http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/02/us-videogames-tetris-idUSTRE5510V020090602|archive-date=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> while he was working for the [[Dorodnitsyn Computing Centre]] of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union]] in Moscow.<ref>[http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/special/tetrishist.html The Tetris saga] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507094323/http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/special/tetrishist.html |date=May 7, 2012 }}. Retrieved August 24, 2007.</ref> He derived its name from combining the Greek numerical prefix ''[[tetra-]]'' (the falling pieces contain 4 segments) and tennis, Pajitnov's favorite sport.<ref name=\"g4_tetra_tennis\">Pajitnov interview, [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]] \"[[Icons (TV series)|Icons]]\", ep. [http://www.g4tv.com/icons/episodes/1314/Tetris.html 305] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050311025939/http://www.g4tv.com/icons/episodes/1314/Tetris.html |date=March 11, 2005 }}, originally aired on April 22, 2004.</ref><ref name=\"vadim\">Gerasimov, Vadim. [http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm Original Tetris: Story and Download] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821183909/http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm |date=August 21, 2006 }}. June 10, 2007.</ref> The name is also used in-game to refer to the play where four lines are cleared at once.\n\n''Tetris'' was the first game to be exported from the Soviet Union to the United States, where it was published by [[Spectrum HoloByte]] for the [[Commodore 64]] and [[IBM PC]]. The game is a popular use of [[tetromino]]es, the four-element case of [[polyomino]]es, which have been used in popular puzzles since at least 1907. (The name for these figures was given by the mathematician [[Solomon W. Golomb]] in 1953.)\n\nThe game, or [[List of Tetris variants|one of its many variants]], is available for nearly every [[video game console]] and computer [[operating system]], as well as on devices such as [[graphing calculator]]s, [[mobile phones]], [[portable media player]]s, [[Personal digital assistant|PDAs]], [[Internet radio device|Network music players]], and as an [[Easter egg (media)|Easter egg]] on non-media products like [[oscilloscope]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eeggs.com/items/39244.html|title=HP 54600B Oscilloscope Easter Eggs|publisher=Eeggs.com|accessdate=November 12, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217031557/http://www.eeggs.com/items/39244.html|archive-date=December 17, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> It has inspired ''Tetris'' serving dishes,<ref>{{cite news|author=Perets, Abbi|title=Tetris-inspired dishware brings the game to dinner|url=https://www.cnet.com/8301-13553_1-10457461-32.html|work=CNet|date=February 22, 2010|access-date=February 25, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225183821/http://www.cnet.com/8301-13553_1-10457461-32.html|archive-date=February 25, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> and it has even been played on the sides of various buildings.<ref>{{cite magazine| last = Grossman| first = Samantha| title = Watch a Giant Game of Tetris Played on a Philadelphia Skyscraper| magazine = [[Time (magazine)|Time]]| date = April 6, 2014| url = http://time.com/50988/giant-tetris-philadelphia-skyscraper/| accessdate = April 7, 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140406160502/http://time.com/50988/giant-tetris-philadelphia-skyscraper/| archive-date = April 6, 2014| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nWhile versions of ''Tetris'' were sold for a range of 1980s home computer platforms as well as [[Arcade game|arcades]], it was the successful [[Tetris (Game Boy)|handheld version]] for the [[Game Boy]], launched in 1989, that established the game to critics and fans as one of the [[greatest video games of all time]]. {{As of|2011|12}}, the games in the franchise had sold 202{{nbsp}}million copies\u2014approximately 70{{nbsp}}million physical units and 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads\u2014making it one of the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchises of all time]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Tetris basic game.gif|thumb|Video of an open-source ''Tetris'' [[Clone (video game)|clone]]]]\n''Tetris'' is primarily composed of a field of play in which pieces of different geometric forms, called \"[[Tetromino|tetriminos]]\", descend from the top of the field.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} During this descent, the player can move the pieces laterally and rotate them until they touch the bottom of the field or land on a piece that had been placed before it.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\">{{cite web |url=https://tetris.com/about-us |title=About ''Tetris'' |publisher=The Tetris Company |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref> The player can neither slow down the falling pieces nor stop them, but can accelerate them in most versions.<ref>''Tetris'' (Game Boy) instruction booklet, p. 4</ref><ref>''Tetris DS'' instruction booklet, p. 6</ref> The objective of the game is to use the pieces to create as many horizontal lines of blocks as possible. When a line is completed, it disappears, and the blocks placed above fall one rank.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> Completing lines grants points, and accumulating a certain number of points moves the player up a level, which increases the number of points granted per completed line.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\">''Tetris'' (Game Boy) instruction booklet, p. 16</ref> In most versions, the speed of the falling pieces increases with each level, leaving the player with less time to think about the placement.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> The player can clear multiple lines at once, which can earn bonus points in some versions.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} It is possible to complete up to four lines simultaneously with the use of the I-shaped tetrimino; this move is called a \"Tetris\", and is the basis of the game's title.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\"/> If the player cannot make the blocks disappear quickly enough, the field will start to fill, and when the pieces reach the top of the field and prevent the arrival of additional pieces, the game ends.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> At the end of each game, the player receives a score based on the number of lines that have been completed.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\"/> The game never ends with the player's victory; the player can only complete as many lines as possible before an inevitable loss. However, in some versions of the game, the player can achieve a \"max-out\" by reaching the highest score that can be displayed (999,999 on a six-digit display).{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} \n\nSince 1996, The Tetris Company has internally defined specifications and guidelines that publishers must adhere to in order to be granted a license to ''Tetris''. The contents of these guidelines establish such elements as the correspondence of buttons and actions, the size of the field of play, the system of rotation, and others.<ref name=\"HistoryOfTetris\">{{cite web |url=https://tetris.com/history-of-tetris |title=History of ''Tetris'' |publisher=The Tetris Company |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"tftt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/interview/11267/tetris-from-the-top-an-interview-with-henk-rogers |title=''Tetris'' from the Top: An Interview with Henk Rogers |author=Metts, Jonathan |website=Nintendo World Report |date=April 6, 2006 |accessdate=April 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Game pieces===\n[[File:Tetrominoes IJLO STZ Worlds.svg|thumb|left|All seven tetriminos using the standard color scheme]]\nThe pieces on which the game of ''Tetris'' is based around are called \"tetriminos\". Pajitnov's original version for the [[Electronika 60]] computer used green brackets to represent the blocks that make up tetriminos.<ref name=\"vadim\"/> Versions of ''Tetris'' on the original Game Boy/Game Boy Color and on most dedicated handheld games use [[monochrome]] or grayscale graphics, but most popular versions use a separate color for each distinct shape. Prior to The Tetris Company's standardization in the early 2000s, those colors varied widely from implementation to implementation.\n\n===Scoring===\nThe scoring formula for the majority of ''Tetris'' products is built on the idea that more difficult line clears should be awarded more points. For example, a single line clear in ''Tetris Zone'' is worth 100 points, clearing four lines at once (known as a ''Tetris'') is worth 800, while each subsequent back-to-back ''Tetris'' is worth 1,200.<ref name=\"tzmanual\">[http://zone.tetris.com/page/manual ''Tetris Zone'' manual] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206023148/http://zone.tetris.com/page/manual |date=February 6, 2009 }} as of November 12, 2008</ref> In conjunction, players can be awarded combos that exist in certain games which reward multiple line clears in quick succession. The exact conditions for triggering combos, and the amount of importance assigned to them, vary from game to game.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nNearly all ''Tetris'' games allow the player to press a button to increase the speed of the current piece's descent or cause the piece to drop and lock into place immediately, known as a \"soft drop\" and a \"hard drop\", respectively. While performing a soft drop, the player can also stop the piece's increased speed by releasing the button before the piece settles into place. Some games only allow either soft drop or hard drop; others have separate buttons for both. Many games award a number of points based on the height that the piece fell before locking, so using the hard drop generally awards more points.\n\n=== Easy spin dispute ===\nAlthough not the first ''Tetris'' game to feature a new kind of ''Tetris'', \"easy spin\" (see ''[[The Next Tetris]]''), also called \"infinite spin\" by critics,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gba/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html |title=Tetris Worlds for Game Boy Advance Review |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=September 5, 2001 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028130427/http://www.gamespot.com/gba/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html |archive-date=October 28, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Tetris Worlds]]'' was the first game to fall under major criticisms for it. Easy spin refers to the property of a Tetromino to stop falling for a moment after left or right movement or rotation, effectively allowing someone to suspend the Tetromino while thinking on where to place it. This feature has been implemented into [[The Tetris Company]]'s official guideline.<ref name=\"tftt\"/> This type of play differs from traditional ''Tetris'' because it takes away the pressure of higher level speed. Some reviewers<ref name=\"gsrev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html|title=Tetris Worlds for PlayStation 2 Review|accessdate=November 12, 2008|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 19, 2002|author1=Jeff Gerstmann|author2=Ryan Davis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130070533/http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html|archive-date=January 30, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> went so far as to say that this mechanism broke the game. The goal in ''Tetris Worlds'', however, is to complete a certain number of lines as fast as possible, so the ability to hold off a piece's placement will not make achieving that goal any faster. Later, GameSpot received \"easy spin\" more openly, saying that \"the infinite spin issue honestly really affects only a few of the single-player gameplay modes in ''Tetris DS'', because any competitive mode requires you to lay down pieces as quickly as humanly possible.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ds/puzzle/tetris/review.html |title=Tetris DS for DS Review \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=March 20, 2006 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805040528/http://www.gamespot.com/ds/puzzle/tetris/review.html |archivedate=August 5, 2011 |df= }}</ref> In response to the issue, [[Henk Rogers]] stated in an interview that infinite spin was an intentional part of the game design, allowing novice players to expend some of their available scoring time to decide on the best placement of a piece. Rogers observed that \"gratuitous spinning\" does not occur in competitive play, as expert players do not require much time to think about where a piece should be placed. A limitation has been placed on infinite lock delay in later games of the franchise, where after a certain amount of inputs i.e.: rotations and movements, the piece will instantly lock itself. This is defaulted to 15 inputs.<ref name=\"tftt\"/>\n\n== History ==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width    = 250\n | image1   = Tetris-VeryFirstVersion.png\n | caption1 = The first version of ''Tetris'', completed in 1984, run on an emulator of the [[Electronika 60]]\n | image2   = Tetris DOS 1986.png\n | caption2 = Screenshot of the 1986 IBM PC version developed by Dmitry Pavlovsky and [[Vadim Gerasimov]]\n | image3   = Tetris screenshot (Amiga, Infogrames).png\n | caption3 = The version designed by Spectrum Holobyte contained Russia-related images (Amiga version screenshot, 1988)\n}}\n\n=== Creation and early popularity ===\n''Tetris'' was created in June 1984 by [[Alexey Pajitnov]], an [[artificial intelligence]] researcher working for the [[Soviet Academy of Sciences]] (now the Russian Academy of Sciences) at the Computer Center in Moscow.<ref name=\"guardian2014\">{{cite news |author=Phil Hoad |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jun/02/how-we-made-tetris |title=Tetris: how we made the addictive computer game &#124; Culture |newspaper=The Guardian |date=June 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621140034/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jun/02/how-we-made-tetris |archive-date=June 21, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Tasked with testing the capabilities of new hardware, Pajitnov would do so by writing simple games for them. He initially considered creating a game around [[pentomino]]es, which featured in puzzle games that he had enjoyed as a child, but felt that it might have been too complicated with twelve different shape variations, so the concept switched to [[tetromino]]es, of which there are seven variants.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /> The [[Electronika 60]] computer used to develop the game had only a text-based display, so the tetrominoes had to consist of pseudo-graphics.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /> Realizing that completed lines resulted in the screen filling up quickly, Pajitnov decided to delete them, creating a key part of ''Tetris'' gameplay.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" />\n\nPajitnov's game proved popular with his colleagues.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /> Academy of Sciences co-workers Dmitry Pavlovsky and [[Vadim Gerasimov]] ported the game to the [[IBM Personal Computer|IBM PC]]. Gerasimov reports that Pajitnov chose the name ''Tetris'' as \"a combination of '[[tetromino]]' and 'tennis'\". From there, the PC game became popular and began spreading around Moscow.<ref name=\"vadim\"/> Unsure of how to publish his game and fearful of the response of the Soviet regime if he did so, Pajitnov took the opportunity offered by [[Perestroika]] and gave the rights to the Soviet government for ten years.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /><ref name=\"alexyinterview\">Boyes, Emma. [http://www.gamespot.com/news/6181946.html Q&A Tetris creator Alexey Pajitnov] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607193954/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6181946.html |date=June 7, 2009 }}. Retrieved October 31, 2007.</ref>\n\n=== Exportation and licensing ===\nPajitnov's boss at the Soviet Academy shared a copy with some colleagues at the SCKI Institute of Computer Science in [[Budapest]], Hungary, where it was ported to the Commodore 64 and Apple II by some of its students. It was at the institute where ''Tetris'' was \"discovered\" by Robert Stein, a man who ran a British software company named Andromeda Software. Stein asked the Institute's director about licensing, and the director told him that the game had come from the Soviet Union. The director had the number to the Soviet Academy's [[Telex]] machine, and Stein used the number to send a message stating that he wanted to acquire the rights to ''Tetris''. The message was forwarded to Pajitnov, and after several weeks of getting translations and proper authorization, Pajitnov sent a reply suggesting that he was interested in a deal. Stein interpreted this as a verbal agreement for him to sub-license ''Tetris'' rights, and he began to make deals with [[Mirrorsoft]] and [[Spectrum HoloByte]] that would allow the latter two to publish ''Tetris'' for computers in their respective regions. There was a problem, however: Stein did not have a signed contract with the Soviet Union. Stein sent a second Telex message to the Academy with his offer for ''Tetris'', and Pajitnov gave a vague, yet positive response. Stein continued to push for a deal with the Soviet Union, but while he was doing so, the Soviet Academy had intervened with the negotiations. The Academy's internal publishing and licensing group, AcademySoft, handled further negotiations with Stein. AcademySoft insisted that the only rights available were the IBM PC rights, and Stein agreed; he would negotiate for future ''Tetris'' rights later.<ref name=\"stts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_fQtxKmgJC8|title=The Story of Tetris}}</ref>\n\nSeveral months had passed since Stein found ''Tetris'' at the Hungarian Institute, and Stein still did not have a signed contract with the Soviet Union for any ''Tetris'' rights. Stein sent a Telex message to the Soviet Union in April 1987 stating that Mirrorsoft and Spectrum HoloByte were going to release their versions of ''Tetris'', but his forcefulness would get him nowhere. Mirrorsoft and Spectrum HoloByte had prepared their versions of ''Tetris'' for release under the assumption that Stein had secured all the rights with the Soviet Union, and Stein finalized his deals with the two companies in June 1987.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\n=== ''Tetris'' is released ===\nSome time before Mirrorsoft's and Spectrum HoloByte's versions of ''Tetris'' were released, Stein received a Telex message from another Soviet organization known as [[Elektronorgtechnica]] (\"Elorg\"). The message stated that Stein was selling ''Tetris'' illegally, and that further negotiations would have to go through them. Elorg learned that researchers at the Soviet Academy, including Pajitnov, were developing computer programs. Elorg met with Pajitnov to see if any of his programs could be sold internationally, and Pajitnov casually mentioned his ''Tetris'' dealings during the meeting. This shocked the Elorg representatives; they demanded that all of the paperwork be handed over immediately and they took over the ''Tetris'' negotiations. Stein flew to Moscow to explain himself at Elorg's request, and the two continued negotiations.<ref name=\"stts\"/> Although nothing was signed with the Soviet Union yet, the computer versions of ''Tetris'' were released in January 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/29/business/new-software-game-it-comes-from-soviet.html|title=New Software Game: It Comes From Soviet|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=1988-01-29}}</ref> The Commodore 64 version had a 26-minute soundtrack composed by game musician Wally Beben. The game's popularity was tremendous; ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' called the game \"deceptively simple and insidiously addictive\".<ref name=\"CGW\">{{Cite news|date=May 1988|last=Wagner|first=Roy| periodical=Computer Gaming World|title=Puzzling Encounters|pages=42\u201343}}</ref> Stein eventually got a deal with Elorg on May 10, 1988.<ref name=\"tl\"/> The deal gave Andromeda the rights to ''Tetris'' for home computers and \"different types of computers\"; the second line was vague enough for Stein to assume that it also referred to systems other than home computers. Stein contacted Mirrorsoft to tell them that the deal was done, and Mirrorsoft inquired about other rights to ''Tetris''. Stein told them that future deals would be coming.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\n=== Henk Rogers enters the picture ===\n[[Henk Rogers]] was first exposed to ''Tetris'' while he was visiting the [[Consumer Electronics Show]] (CES) in Las Vegas in January 1988. Phil Adam, the president of Spectrum HoloByte, stood on the showroom floor displaying ''Tetris'' to a line of attendees that included Rogers. Although Rogers considered ''Tetris'' to be the quietest game at the show, he was eventually hooked and pursued the rights to the game. Rogers learned that Gilman Louie, the CEO of Spectrum HoloByte, was going to Japan to try to shop the game. Louie pitched ''Tetris'' to [[ASCII]], but they turned it down, thinking it was \"too retro\". Louie eventually found Rogers and the two signed a letter of intent for Rogers' company, [[Blue Planet Software|Bullet-Proof Software]], to publish Tetris in Japan for every platform Rogers could think of, including [[Nintendo]]'s Famicom. Later on, Louie contacted Rogers to tell him that while he could have the Japanese home computer rights to Tetris, he would have to contact [[Atari Games]] if he wanted the Famicom and Japanese arcade rights. Engineers at Atari Games got addicted to the PC version of ''Tetris'', and that encouraged the company to get the console and arcade rights from Mirrorsoft in exchange for the PC rights to ''[[Blasteroids]]''. Atari Games initially declined to sub-license any rights to Rogers when he first contacted them. Despite this, Rogers flew out to California and camped out in the Atari Games parking lot, waiting for an opportunity to talk to its president, Hideyuki Nakajima. One day as Nakajima was leaving, Rogers made his pitch to him. After hearing it, Nakajima agreed to a meeting. The two had a meeting over a sushi dinner, and at the meeting, Nakajima told Rogers that while the Famicom rights were up for grabs, he couldn't have the Japanese arcade rights since they were already sold to [[Sega]]. Steve Hanawa, a representative of Sega of America at the time, learned about ''Tetris'' during the development of ''Monopoly''; the team developing the title was also developing a PC version of ''Tetris'', and Hanawa's addiction to the game led him to get Sega of Japan to license the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sega-16.com/2011/10/interview-steve-hanawa/|title=Interview: Steve Hanawa (SOA Director of R&D}}</ref> Regardless, Rogers paid Atari $300,000 for the Famicom rights.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nBullet-Proof Software had initially only received about 40,000 orders. Henk Rogers contacted [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]], the president of Nintendo at the time, in hopes that he could help him advertise the title. Yamauchi was interested, so he passed down Tetris to [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]. Days later, Yamauchi sent a letter to Miyamoto asking if Tetris was a good game. Miyamoto said it was, and when Yamauchi asked why, Miyamoto said, \"Because your accountants and secretaries are playing it\". After this happened, Yamauchi agreed to push sales of Tetris. Orders increased from 40,000 to over 200,000.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nBullet-Proof Software's home computer versions of ''Tetris'' were released on November 18, 1988,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000823075838/http://www.bps.co.jp/04_products/index71.html|title=Products: Personal Computers|publisher=Bullet-Proof Software}}</ref> while the Famicom version was released on December 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000823075808/http://www.bps.co.jp/04_products/index31.html|title=Products: Family Computer|publisher=Bullet-Proof Software}}</ref> The Famicom version would go on to sell over 2 million copies in Japan,<ref name=\"hist\"/>\n\nSega's arcade version for [[Sega System 16]] and System E arcade boards were released in December 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sega-interactive.co.jp/product/9260|title=\u30c6\u30c8\u30ea\u30b9|publisher=Sega}}</ref><ref>{{KLOV game|10082|Tetris (Sega)}}</ref> It won the Japanese [[Gamest]] Award for [[Game of the Year]] the following year, and it was number-three in ''[[Famitsu|Famicom Ts\u016bshin]]''{{'}}s August and September 1989 arcade earnings charts.<ref>''[[Famitsu|Famicom Ts\u016bshin]]'', issue 19 (September 15, 1989)</ref> It rose to number two in October 1989, overtaking [[Namco]]'s [[racing video game]] ''[[Winning Run]]''.<ref>''[[Famitsu|Famicom Ts\u016bshin]]'', issue 22 (October 27, 1989)</ref>\n\n=== Licensing issues ===\n{{main|Tetris (NES video game)|Tetris (Game Boy video game)}}\nIn December 1988, Rogers met with the president of Nintendo of America at the time, [[Minoru Arakawa]] at NOA's headquarters to discuss the possibility of ''Tetris'' being one of the launch titles for the upcoming [[Game Boy]]. Arakawa was intrigued; he was aware of the success of the Famicom version of ''Tetris'' in Japan. Rogers contacted Robert Stein under the assumption that he had the handheld rights and offered him $25,000 in advance for them. While this was happening, Mirrorsoft had contacted Stein to see if he could give them those same rights. Stein was wishy-washy with his response; he told Rogers that he would have to check with Elorg.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nAs time passed, Rogers grew suspicious of Stein and then got word that Gilman Louie was trying to sell the handheld rights to Nintendo. When Arakawa contacted Rogers about it, Rogers told him that Louie didn't actually have the handheld rights and that he needed Arakawa to give him a chance to finalize the deal. Figuring it would be easier to talk to Elorg himself to try to get the handheld rights instead of waiting for Stein to get back to him, Rogers headed to Elorg's headquarters. When Mirrorsoft caught wind of Nintendo's interest in the handheld rights to ''Tetris'', their parent company, the Maxwell Corporation, sent its joint managing director Kevin Maxwell to Elorg's headquarters.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nOn February 22, 1989, Stein, Rogers, and Maxwell headed to Elorg's headquarters to negotiate with Elorg about the handheld rights to Tetris. While Stein and Maxwell booked meetings with Elorg in advance, Rogers did not. Rogers was the first to arrive there; he asked someone at Elorg about who he could talk to about Tetris as soon as he arrived. He was directed to Nikolai Belikov, Elorg's managing director. Belikov had been hired by Elorg to sort out the licensing problems for ''Tetris''; Elorg was not getting paid. Rogers introduced himself by taking out a copy of the Famicom version of ''Tetris'' and said that he was the \"biggest publisher of Tetris in the world\". To Rogers' shock, Belikov told him that Elorg had not given any console rights to ''Tetris'' to anyone. Rogers told Belikov about the chain of licensees that fot him the rights, but Belikov told him that Elorg only gave the rights to Tetris to Andromeda Software, and that those rights were for home computers. After some discussion, Rogers and Belikov set up a meeting for the following day.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nStein's meeting with Belikov was scheduled to start, and Rogers had barely missed Stein as he was leaving. Stein had planned the meeting with the intent of getting the handheld rights to Tetris. However, what happened instead was that Belikov added an amendment to the contract between Elorg and Andromeda and that Stein agreed to look over the amended contract for a few days. The meeting with Maxwell began after Stein had left. Belikov showed Maxwell a copy of the Famicom version of ''Tetris'' and asked him what it was. Maxwell said that it may be a pirated version. The meeting resulted in Mirrorsoft getting a right of first refusal to any new rights to ''Tetris'', and it was confirmation for Elorg that the console rights to ''Tetris'' were never given to anyone.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nOn February 23, 1989, the scheduled meeting between Rogers and Elorg began. The two parties were at opposite ends of a long table; Rogers was on one end while Belikov, Tetris creator Alexey Pajitnov, and other Elorg members were on the other end. Rogers started things off by giving the Elorg members a \"crash course\" of the video game market. After that, Elorg showed Rogers the original contract they had with Robert Stein of Andromeda Software. Rogers looked through it and found the line that had caused the licensing issues - the contract stated that Andromeda had the rights to Tetris for \"different types of computers\". Stein assumed that this also meant things like game consoles. After that, Rogers offered the Elorg members a fixed amount of money for each cartridge sold. Belikov asked Rogers to make a formal offer for the handheld rights after hearing the other offer. Stein met up with Belikov that same day with the signed contract, but Belikov stated that Elorg was not ready to hand over the handheld rights to Tetris yet. Rogers met up with Belikov a day later with the formal offer and gave it a one week deadline.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nSometime later, Belikov contacted Rogers to tell him that Maxwell was bidding for the handheld rights. Rogers told Belikov that although he couldn't give him as much money as Maxwell, he could at least give him honesty and the promise to pay for each cartridge. Several days later, Rogers presented Elorg with a finalized contract and walked through its details. Belikov signed it, and it resulted in Rogers and Nintendo getting the handheld rights to Tetris.<ref name=\"stts\"/> The results of the licensing deal put Bullet-Proof Software as a licensor and Nintendo as a sub-licensor. On top of that, ''Tetris'' had been bundled with every Game Boy.<ref name=guardian020609/> Rogers later said, \"''Tetris'' made Game Boy and Game Boy made ''Tetris''.\"<ref name=\"guardian2014\" />\n\n=== Legal battles ===\n{{main|Tetris (Atari)}}\nAfter Henk Rogers successfully got the handheld rights to ''Tetris'', Elorg told him they would like for him to make an offer for the console rights to ''Tetris''. There would be trouble ahead: Mirrorsoft had the right of first refusal to any new rights to ''Tetris'', and Atari could potentially go after Rogers if they found out a deal was being made. When Rogers left Moscow, he contacted Nintendo to tell them that the console rights were available. Nintendo told Rogers to go back to Moscow with their offer of $5 million in advance and to contact them if he thinks a deal could happen. As soon as Nintendo found out a deal was possible, Minoru Arakawa and [[Howard Lincoln]] headed to Elorg's headquarters to secure the console rights. As soon as Nintendo got them, they sent a cease-and-desist letter to Atari Games.<ref name=\"stts\"/>\n\nDespite the letter, Atari Games went through with releasing their NES version of ''Tetris'' through their subsidiary, [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]]. They distributed it under the name ''TET\u042fIS: The Soviet Mind Game'' (with [[faux Cyrillic]] typography incorporating the [[Ya (Cyrillic)|Cyrillic letter Ya]]). Atari Games sued Nintendo, believing they had the rights. After four weeks on the shelf, the courts ruled that Nintendo was the only company which had the rights to ''Tetris'' on home game systems. The amended contract with Andromeda had invalidated any \"console rights\" given out. Tengen's ''TET\u042fIS'' was recalled with an unknown number of copies sold.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=From Russia with Litigation|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=26|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=February 1997|page=42}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|year=2002|title=The Wish List|journal=Edge Presents Retro|id=|url=|quote=}}</ref>\n\nSega had planned to release a [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive]] version of ''Tetris'' on April 15, 1989, but they cancelled its release<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19890501p.pdf#page=14|title=Game Machine: \"Nintendo Offers Home Video Game 'Tetris'\"|publisher=Amusement Press|date=1989-05-01}}</ref> during Atari's licensing issues, resulting in fewer than ten copies being printed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/you-could-own-this-copy-of-tetris-for-only-1-000-000-5822380 |title=You Could Own This Copy of Tetris for Only $1,000,000 |first=Michael |last=McWhertor |work=Kotaku |date=July 18, 2011 | access-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604193847/https://kotaku.com/you-could-own-this-copy-of-tetris-for-only-1-000-000-5822380 |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A new port of the arcade version by M2 was included in the [[Sega Genesis Mini]] microconsole, released in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/06/04/final-12-genesis-mini-games-list-includes-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-versions-of-tetris |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604221811/https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/06/04/final-12-genesis-mini-games-list-includes-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-versions-of-tetris |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tetris NES play.png|thumb|right|250px|A-Type game screenshot of the official [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] version of ''Tetris'']]\nNintendo released their NES version of ''Tetris'' in November 1989. It sold 8 million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"tl\">{{Cite episode | title = Tetris: From Russia With Love | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0074pz0 | series = BBC Four | credits = Director/Producer: Magnus Temple; Executive Producer: Nick Southgate | network = [[BBC]] | station = [[BBC Four]] | date = 2004 | time = 51:23 | quote = The real winners were Nintendo. To date, Nintendo dealers across the world have sold 8 million ''Tetris'' cartridges on the Nintendo Entertainment system. | access-date = September 4, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160101183339/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0074pz0 | archivedate = January 1, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref>  Nintendo's NES version lacked the side-by-side 2-player option featured in Tengen's version. ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' reviewed this version in its November / December 1989 edition. The [[Classic Tetris World Championship]] commenced in 2010 and uses the Nintendo version of ''Tetris''.\n\nNintendo released the game again for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System ([[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]]) along with [[Dr. Mario]]. The new version used different colors than older versions, and makes the squares look more connected. This version is similar to the version released on the NES.\n\n=== The Tetris Company ===\n{{Main|The Tetris Company}}\nIn 1996, the rights to the game reverted from the Russian state to Pajitnov himself, who previously had made very little money from the game.<ref name=guardian020609/> That year, [[The Tetris Company]] was founded, claiming to hold [[copyright registration]]s for ''Tetris'' products in the U.S.<ref>Blue Planet Software, Inc. v. Pajitnov, 334 F. Supp 2d 425 (S.D.N.Y. 2004).</ref><ref>See, e.g., Copyright Registration Nos. PAu 1-214-036; PAu 1-214-035; PA 412\u2013169; PA 412\u2013170, among others.</ref> and taking out trademark registrations for ''Tetris'' in almost every country in the world.<ref>See, e.g., Trademark Registration Nos. 1,753,062 (USA); 1,657,499 (USA); 1,742,325 (USA); 1,382,544 (UK); 1,382,543 (UK); 507644 (Taiwan); 498703 (Taiwan); 098,381 (Peru); 097, 244 (Peru); 266/36 (Saudi Arabia), among others.</ref> They have licensed the brand to a number of companies, and the U.S. Court of International Trade and the U.S. Customs have at times issued seizure orders to preclude unlicensed ''Tetris''-like games from being imported into the U.S.,<ref>See [https://web.archive.org/web/20090827075506/http://www.cit.uscourts.gov/slip_op/Slip_op00/00-27.pdf Luxury Int\u2019l, Inc. v. U.S., No. 99-02-00093, Slip Op. 00-27] (Ct. Int\u2019l Trade 2000), holding that Luxury violated Customs' administrative procedure; U.S. Customs Service Memorandum Order, ENF-4-02-RR:IT:IP 470343 GFM (December 19, 2000); U.S. Customs Service Memorandum Order, ENF4-02-RR:IT:IP 469107 GFM (July 31, 2000).</ref> though bulletins circulated by the U.S. Copyright Office state that copyright does not apply to the rules of a game.<ref name=\"17usc102\">U.S. Copyright Office. [http://www.copyright.gov/title17/92chap1.html Title 17, United States Code, section 102] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518093808/http://www.copyright.gov/title17/92chap1.html |date=May 18, 2011 }}. Retrieved March 12, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"fl108\">U.S. Copyright Office. [http://www.copyright.gov/fls/fl108.pdf \"Publication FL-108: Games.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625004618/http://www.copyright.gov/fls/fl108.pdf |date=June 25, 2009 }} June 2008. Explanation of how {{usc|17|102}}(b) limits the extent to which copyright applies to the rules of a game. Retrieved June 2, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn late 1997<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abednarz.net/wp/category/tetris-copyright/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123070027/http://abednarz.net/wp/category/tetris-copyright/ |url-status=dead|archive-date=January 23, 2009 |title=The Tetris Company's Activities |author=Bednarz, Andrew James |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |df= }}</ref> and mid-2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expertreviews.co.uk/general/90129/tetris-blocks-mac-quinn-game |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006212333/http://www.expertreviews.co.uk/general/90129/tetris-blocks-mac-quinn-game |url-status=dead|archive-date=October 6, 2011 |title=Tetris blocks Mac Quinn game |date=July 11, 2006 |publisher=Expert Reviews |author=Aughton, Simon |accessdate=June 23, 2012}}</ref> TTC's legal counsel sent [[cease and desist]] letters to Web sites on the basis of ''Tetris''-type games infringing the \"Tetris\" trademark, [[trade dress]], and/or \"[[look and feel]]\" copyright. Gerasimov removed his 1988 version of the game from his website in October 2003, in response to a demand from counsel for The Tetris Company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vadim.www.media.mit.edu/tetris.htm|title=Tetris: the story|date=November 28, 2003|accessdate=September 18, 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031128090208/http://vadim.www.media.mit.edu/tetris.htm|archivedate=November 28, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vadim.www.media.mit.edu/Yahoo1.htm|title=Notice of Infringement|accessdate=September 18, 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031222204849/http://vadim.www.media.mit.edu/Yahoo1.htm|archivedate=December 22, 2003}}</ref> He resumed making it available in August 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm|title=Tetris Story|date=August 21, 2006|accessdate=September 18, 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821183909/http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm|archivedate=August 21, 2006}}</ref> Around 2009, TTC and Tetris Holding LLC brought legal action against BioSocia, Inc., on the grounds that BioSocia's \"Blockles\" game infringed on proprietary rights that were held by TTC and Tetris Holding LLC.<ref name=\"blockles_case\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090910006464/en/Resolution-Litigation-%E2%80%9CBlockles%E2%80%9D-Announced-Tetris-Holding-LLC|title=Resolution of Litigation Regarding \"Blockles\" Announced by Tetris Holding, The Tetris Company, BioSocia, Inc. and Charles Forman|publisher=[[BusinessWire]]|date=September 10, 2009|accessdate=February 18, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708105430/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090910006464/en/Resolution-Litigation-%E2%80%9CBlockles%E2%80%9D-Announced-Tetris-Holding-LLC|archive-date=July 8, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 10, 2009, the legal case against BioSocia was resolved, with BioSocia agreeing to discontinue making the \"Blockles\" game available to the public.<ref name=\"blockles_case\"/> In May 2010, TTC's legal counsel sent cease and desist letters to Google insisting that 35 ''Tetris'' clones be removed from the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[Android Market|Market]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2010/06/google-blocks-tetris-clones-from-android-market/ |title=Google blocks Tetris clones from Android market |website=Ars Technica |author=Paul, Ryan |date=June 2, 2010 |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202210616/http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2010/06/google-blocks-tetris-clones-from-android-market/ |archive-date=December 2, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> A US District Court judge ruled in June 2012 that the ''Tetris'' clone \"Mino\" from Xio Interactive infringed on The Tetris Company's copyrights by replicating such elements as the playfield dimensions and the shapes of the blocks.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-06/20/tetris-clone-ruling |title=US judge declares Tetris clone 'infringing' |journal=Wired UK |author=Brown, Mark |date=June 20, 2012 |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623025355/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-06/20/tetris-clone-ruling |archive-date=June 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In addition, it was ruled that Tetris Holding LLC's trade dress had been infringed because \"Mino\" had replicated the form and brightly colored style of the ''Tetris'' Tetriminos and the higher-than-wide rectangular ''Tetris'' playfield.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Attack Of The Clones: Copyright Protection For Video Game Developers |journal=Loyola of Los Angeles Entertainment Law Review |volume=33 Rev 137 |issue=2 (2013) |pages=166\u2013167 |last=Casillas |first=Brian |url=https://digitalcommons.lmu.edu/elr/vol33/iss2/2/ |accessdate=March 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306235034/https://digitalcommons.lmu.edu/elr/vol33/iss2/2/ |archive-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>''\n\n===Newer ''Tetris'' variations===\nIn 2014, in conjunction with the 30th anniversary of the series, Sega released ''[[Puyo Puyo Tetris]]'', a multi-platform game that blends gameplay elements of both the ''Tetris'' and ''[[Puyo Puyo (series)|Puyo Puyo]]'' franchises.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u300c\u3077\u3088\u3077\u3088\u30c6\u30c8\u30ea\u30b9\u300d\u306e\u767a\u58f2\u65e5\u304c2014\u5e742\u67086\u65e5\u306b\u6c7a\u5b9a\u3002\u300c\u30d5\u30a3\u30ae\u30e5\u30a2\u4ed8\u304d3DS/3DS LL\u30ab\u30d0\u30fc\u30bb\u30c3\u30c8\u300d\u3082\u540c\u6642\u767a\u58f2|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/233/G023319/20131028005/|website=4Gamer|accessdate=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221015510/http://www.4gamer.net/games/233/G023319/20131028005/|archive-date=February 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 13, 2019, Nintendo announced and released a new version of the classic game called [[Tetris 99]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SCME2yPJKWk|title=Tetris 99 Announcement in the 2.13.19 Nintendo Direct|last=Nintendo|date=February 13, 2019|website=Youtube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320093729/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SCME2yPJKWk|archive-date=March 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Tetris 99 features a battle royale-style game mode where 99 players play in the same match. In addition to complying with the Tetris Guideline, this version of the game features a unique mechanic known as \"badges.\" Badges lessen the severity of attacks received and amplifies the attacks sent. Players can gain badges by knocking out others who have them. Later in 2019, the 2.0 update introduced \"Invictus\" mode, which is more difficult and competitive than the original version.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/tetris-99-s-2-0-update-includes-a-new-invictus-mode-565827.phtml|title=Tetris 99's 2.0 update includes a new 'Invictus' mode|website=Destructoid|language=english|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> Tetris 99 is only available on the [[Nintendo Switch]].\n\nBased on the success of ''Tetris 99'', the Tetris Company and [[N3TWORK]] are developing ''Tetris Royale'', an [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version of ''Tetris'' that will include a [[battle royale game|battle royale]] mode for 100 players, along with other solo and multiplayer modes. It is expected for release in 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/28/19102611/tetris-royale-mobile-n3twork-nintendo-tetris-99 | title = Tetris Royale, a 100-player battle royale, is coming to mobile devices | first = Dami | last = Lee | date = June 28, 2019 | accessdate = June 28, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190628165710/https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/28/19102611/tetris-royale-mobile-n3twork-nintendo-tetris-99 | archive-date = June 28, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref>{{needsupdate|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Variations ==\n{{more citations needed section|date=June 2012}}\n[[File:Tetris on an iPod.jpg|250px|thumb|A [[iPod classic|5th generation]] [[iPod]] running ''Tetris'' (2006)]]\n\n''Tetris'' has been subject to many changes throughout releases since the release of its first version in 1984. Recent ''Tetris'' games have emphasized pace rather than endurance. Older releases such as Game Boy or NES ''Tetris'' offer records according to points. Since the meter for points is restricted to a specific number of digits, these games' records can be \"maxed out\" by an experienced player. The next big Game Boy release after ''Tetris'', ''Tetris DX'', in marathon mode\u2014comparable to mode A in previous releases\u2014allowed an additional digit for the point meter. Even so, players still maxed it to 9,999,999&nbsp;points after hours of play. For ''[[The New Tetris]]'', world record competitors have spent over 12&nbsp;hours playing the same game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twingalaxies.com/index.aspx?c=12&id=635 |title=Welcome to Twin Galaxies |publisher=Twingalaxies.com |accessdate=November 12, 2008 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080604221115/http://www.twingalaxies.com/index.aspx?c=12&id=635 |archivedate=June 4, 2008 }}</ref> In ''Tetris DX'' and ''The New Tetris'', the new modes sprint and ultra were added. These modes require the player to act under a timer, either to gain the most lines or points in that time. Releases like ''Tetris Worlds'' removed point records. This particular game kept records by how fast a certain number of lines could be cleared depending on the level. Critics of ''Tetris Worlds'' said it was flawed by virtue of the ability of a piece to hover over the bottom for as long as a player needs.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/>\n\nMany different modes of play have been added in recent years. Modes appearing in more than one major release include classic marathon (game A), sprint (otherwise game B or 40 lines), ultra, square, and cascade.\n\nThe field dimension of ''Tetris'' is perhaps the least deviated among releases: almost always 10 cells wide by 20 high. Some releases on handheld platforms with small screens have smaller fields; for example, the ''Tetris Jr.'' [[Handheld electronic game|keychain game]] has 8 by 12, and ''Tetris'' for Game Boy has 10 by 18.\n\nTraditionally, blocks spawn within the four most central columns and the two highest rows. The ''I'' Tetrimino occupies columns 4, 5, 6 and 7, the ''O'' Tetrimino occupies columns 5 and 6, and the remaining 5 Tetriminos occupy columns 4, 5 and 6 (or in some, especially older, versions, 5, 6 and 7). In some more recent games, pieces spawn above the visible playfield.\n\nIn traditional games, a level-up would occur once every ten lines are cleared. In some newer games such as ''Tetris Worlds'', the number of lines required varies upon each new level. After a level-up, points awarded are increased and the blocks fall slightly faster. For example, NES ''Tetris'' operates at 60 frames per second. At level 0, a piece falls one step every 48 frames, and at level 19, a piece falls one step every 2 frames.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} Level increments either terminate at a certain point (Game Boy ''Tetris'' tops off at level 20) or increase forever yet not in speed after a certain point. NES ''Tetris'' will level up in speed until level 29 (due to limitations of the game's engine, pieces are not capable of dropping faster than this), but tool-assisted emulation will show that the level indicator increases indefinitely\u2014eventually leading to a glitch where the meter displays non-numeric characters. Modern games such as ''Tetris the Grand Master'' or ''Tetris Worlds'', at their highest levels, opt to drop a piece more than one row per frame. Pieces will appear to reach the bottom as soon as they spawn. As a result, these games have a delay that lets the player slide the piece on the bottom for a moment to help deal with an otherwise unplayable fall speed. In some games, the hover time is regenerated after a piece is moved or rotated.\n\nSoft drops were first implemented in Nintendo releases of ''Tetris'' so that pieces would be able to drop faster while not locking as to slide into gaps. The other option is hard dropping, which originated in early PC games such as ''Microsoft Tetris'', a game developed by Dave Edson and bundled with [[Microsoft Entertainment Pack]]. With hard dropping, a piece falls and locks in one frame. Newer ''Tetris'' games feature both options. Some games have their locking roles reversed, with soft dropping making the pieces drop faster and locking down, and hard dropping making the pieces drop instantly but not lock.\n\nSingle direction rotation is an older restriction that has since been ruled out in nearly every new official release by the favor of separate buttons for clockwise and one for counter clockwise rotation. In traditional games, the unsymmetrical vertical orientation I-, Z-, and S-pieces will fill the same columns for each clockwise and counter clockwise rotation. Some games vary this by allowing two possible column orientations: one for counter clockwise and one for clockwise rotations. Double rotation\u2014only seen in progressive clones such as ''Quadra'' and ''DTET''\u2014rotates the piece 180\u00b0.\n\nOne of the features most appreciated by skilled players is ''wall kick'' or the ability to rotate the pieces even if these touch the left or right walls. In the NES version, for example, if a Z piece is \"vertically\" aligned and falling touching the left wall, the player cannot rotate the piece, giving the impression that the rotate buttons are locked. In this situation, the player has to move the piece one position to the right before rotating it, losing precious time. Proper implementations of wall kick first appeared in the arcade version of ''Tetris'' by Atari Games.\n\nPiece preview allows a look at the next piece to enter the field. This feature has been implemented since the earliest games, though in those early games, having the preview turned on made the score increase more slowly.\n\n== Variants ==\n{{Main|List of Tetris variants}}\n\nSeveral ''Tetris'' variants exist. Some feature alternate rules and pieces, some feature alternate topologies or dimensions, and others have completely different gameplay.\n\nA popular variant called \"The Grand Master\" eventually becomes so fast players have to use every second of time optimally, and it even has a mode dubbed \"Invisible Tetris\", where the blocks are only shown when falling \u2013 revealed when the game is over.\n\nBecause of its popularity and the relatively simple code required to produce the game, a game with nearly the same rules as ''Tetris'' is often used as a [[Hello world program|hello world]] project for programmers coding for a new system or programming language. This has resulted in the availability of a large number of [[Porting|ports]] for different platforms.\nFor instance, [[\u03bcTorrent]] and [[Emacs|GNU Emacs]] contain similar shape-stacking games as easter eggs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eeggs.com/items/47291.html |title=uTorrent Easter Egg: Tetris in uTorrent |publisher=Eeggs.com |date=March 16, 2006 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121121044523/http://www.eeggs.com/items/47291.html |archive-date=November 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=poenn |url=http://hints.macworld.com/article.php?story=20050103201954271 |title=macosxhints.com \u2013 Play Tetris in Terminal via emacs |publisher=Hints.macworld.com |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522153944/http://hints.macworld.com/article.php?story=20050103201954271 |archive-date=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== End of play ==\nPlayers lose a typical game of ''Tetris'' when they can no longer keep up with the increasing speed, or when the player can not find a timely solution to the Tetriminos they've been given and the Tetriminos stack up to the top of the playing field. This is commonly referred to as \"topping out\".\n\n=== Infinite gameplay impossibility ===\nThe question ''Would it be possible to play forever?'' was first considered in a thesis by John Brzustowski in 1992.<ref>John Brzustowski. [https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/3263/ubc_1992_spring_brzustowski_john.pdf?sequence=1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016151137/https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/3263/ubc_1992_spring_brzustowski_john.pdf?sequence=1 |date=October 16, 2013 }}. Retrieved October 16, 2013.</ref> The conclusion reached was that the game is statistically doomed to end. The reason has to do with the S and Z Tetriminos. If a player receives a sufficiently large sequence of alternating S and Z Tetriminos, the na\u00efve gravity used by the standard game eventually forces the player to leave holes on the board. The holes will necessarily stack to the top and, ultimately, end the game. If the pieces are distributed randomly, this sequence will eventually occur. Thus, if a game with, for example, an ideal, uniform, uncorrelated [[Random number generation|random number generator]] is played long enough, any player will top out.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061209110731/http://www.math.uic.edu/~burgiel/Tetris/explanation.html Dr. Burgiel's Tetris Research Page, Explanation]. Retrieved February 25, 2007.</ref><ref>Heidi Burgiel. [http://www.geom.umn.edu/%7Eburgiel/Tetris/tetris.PS How to Lose at Tetris] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030513033006/http://www.geom.umn.edu/~burgiel/Tetris/tetris.PS |date=May 13, 2003 }}, Mathematical Gazette, vol. 81, pp. 194\u2013200 1997</ref>\n\nIn practice, this does not occur in most ''Tetris'' variants. Some [[List of Tetris variants|variants]] allow the player to choose to play with only S and Z Tetriminos, and a good player may survive well over 150 consecutive Tetriminos this way. On an implementation with an ideal uniform randomizer, the probability at any given time of the next 150 Tetriminos being only S and Z is ({{sfrac|2|7}})<sup>150</sup> (approximately {{val|2e-82}}). Most implementations use a [[pseudorandom number generator]] to generate the sequence of Tetriminos, and such an S\u2013Z sequence is almost certainly not contained in the sequence produced by the 32-bit [[linear congruential generator]] in many implementations (which has roughly {{val|4.2e9}} states). The \"evil\" algorithm in ''Bastet'' (an unofficial variant) often starts a game with a series of more than seven Z pieces.\n\nModern versions of ''Tetris'' released after 2001 use a bag-style randomizer that guarantees players will never receive more than four S or Z pieces in a row. This is one of the \"Indispensable Rules\" enforced by the ''Tetris Guideline'' that all officially licensed ''Tetris'' games must follow.<ref name=\"tftt\"/>\n\nRecent versions of ''Tetris'' such as ''Tetris Worlds'' allow the player to repeatedly rotate a block once it hits the bottom of the playfield without it locking into place (see [[#Easy spin dispute|Easy spin dispute]], above). This permits a player to play for an infinite amount of time, though not necessarily to land an infinite number of blocks.\n\n== Computational complexity ==\nIn [[computer science]], it is common to analyze the [[Computational complexity theory|computational complexity]] of problems, including real life problems and games. It was proven that for the \"offline\" version of ''Tetris'' (the player knows the complete sequence of pieces that will be dropped, i.e. there is no hidden information) the following objectives are [[NP-complete]]:\n* Maximizing the number of rows cleared while playing the given piece sequence.\n* Maximizing the number of pieces placed before a loss occurs.\n* Maximizing the number of simultaneous clearing of four rows.\n* Minimizing the height of the highest filled grid square over the course of the sequence.\n\nAlso, it is [[Hardness of approximation|difficult to even approximately solve]] the first, second, and fourth problem.  It is [[NP-hard]], given an initial gameboard and a sequence of ''p'' pieces, to approximate the first two problems to within a factor of {{nowrap|''p''<sup>1 \u2212 ''\u03b5''</sup>}} for any constant {{nowrap|''\u03b5'' > 0}}.\nIt is NP-hard to approximate the last problem within a factor of {{nowrap|2 \u2212 ''\u03b5''}} for any constant {{nowrap|''\u03b5'' > 0}}.\n\nTo prove NP-completeness, it was shown that there is a polynomial [[Reduction (complexity)|reduction]] between the [[3-partition problem]], which is also NP-complete, and the ''Tetris'' problem.<ref>{{cite conference|url=http://erikdemaine.org/papers/Tetris_COCOON2003/paper.pdf|title=Tetris is Hard, Even to Approximate|last1=Demaine|first1=Erik D.|last2=Hohenberger|first2=Susan|last3=Liben-Nowell|first3=David|date=July 25\u201328, 2003|conference=Proceedings of the 9th International Computing and Combinatorics Conference (COCOON 2003)|conferenceurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105042734/http://www.cs.montana.edu/bhz/cocoon03.html|location=Big Sky, Montana|access-date=December 18, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613201613/http://erikdemaine.org/papers/Tetris_COCOON2003/paper.pdf|archive-date=June 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{See also|Korobeiniki#Tetris arrangements and modern cover versions|Tetris (Game Boy video game)#Music}}\n\n=== Game Boy version ===\n* Music A has become a well-known song in its own right. It is an instrumental arrangement of a Russian folk tune called \"[[Korobeiniki]]\", which has been covered by UK dance band [[Doctor Spin]], US alternative rock band [[Ozma (band)|Ozma]], [[Tokyo Ska Paradise Orchestra]], [[Basshunter]], Doctor P, and the German [[techno]] group [[Scooter (band)|Scooter]] on their 2007 album ''[[Jumping All Over the World]]''. It was also sampled in \"21 Concepts\" by [[MC Lars]]. Music A and B are also remixed and arranged for ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'', and can be selected for the stage ''[[Luigi's Mansion]]'', as well as being used in custom stages. The remixes were brought back in [[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U|''Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS'' and ''Wii U'']], Music A playing in ''Luigi's Mansion'' and custom stages in the Wii U version and being one of the bonus songs to play in the 3DS exclusive \"Smash Run\" mode, and Music B playing in \"Wuhu Island\" from ''[[Wii Sports Resort]]'' and in custom stages, Music A and B yet again were brought back for ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'' and can be played on the stages \"Summit\" from ''[[Ice Climber]]'', \"Hanenbow\" from ''[[Electroplankton]]'', ''[[Balloon Fight]]'', \"Living Room\" from ''[[Nintendogs]]'', ''[[Find Mii]]'', ''[[Tomodachi Life]]'', ''[[PictoChat]] 2'', ''[[Duck Hunt]]'', ''[[Wrecking Crew (video game)|Wrecking Crew]]'', ''[[Pilotwings]]'', Wuhu Island and custom stages. The song has also been remixed for two dance games, under the name \"Pumptris Quattro\" in ''[[Pump It Up NX2]]'' and \"Happy-hopper\" in ''[[Dance Maniax]] 2nd Mix''. [[Ronan Murray]] has recorded an arrangement of the tune for [[pipe organ]]. The A theme was adapted by Australian musical group [[Flap!]], with original lyrics added, on their debut album ''Flap!''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/artist/flap!/id410490346 |title=iTunes - Music - Flap! |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |accessdate=July 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218023052/https://itunes.apple.com/au/artist/flap!/id410490346 |archive-date=December 18, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Music B is an original track by [[Hirokazu Tanaka]], the game's sound designer. \n* Music C is an arrangement of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s [[French Suites, BWV 812-817|French Suite No. 3 In B Minor, BWV 814, IV. Menuett \u2013 Trio]].\n\n=== Nintendo Entertainment System version ===\n* Music 1 in Nintendo's NES version is \"Dance of the Sugar Plum Fairy\", a tune noted to be scene 14c of act two of ''[[The Nutcracker]]'', composed by [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]].\n* One song in the [[Blue Planet Software|BPS]] and [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]] versions is the [[Kalinka (song)|\"Kalinka\"]] (or Karinka, as referred in-game), a famous Russian song written by [[Ivan Larionov|Ivan Petrovich Larionov]].\n* The victory song playing while the rocket blasts off is George's Bizet's \"Les Toreadors\" from ''Carmen'' Suite No. 1.\n\n=== Atari version ===\nAtari's arcade version of ''Tetris'', and its NES port by subsidiary Tengen have original pieces composed by Brad Fuller, as well as traditional Russian tunes also arranged by Fuller.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vgmpf.com/Wiki/index.php?title=Tetris:_Tengen_%28NES%29 |title=Tetris: Tengen (NES) - Videogame Music Preservation Foundation Wiki |publisher=Vgmpf.com |date=August 15, 2013 |accessdate=July 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316201250/http://www.vgmpf.com/Wiki/index.php?title=Tetris:_Tengen_%28NES%29 |archive-date=March 16, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Cognitive effects ==\n{{See also|Tetris effect}}\nAccording to research from Dr. Richard Haier, ''et al.'' prolonged ''Tetris'' activity can also lead to more efficient brain activity during play.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Richard J Haier|author2=Sherif Karama|author3=Leonard Leyba|author4=Rex E Jung|title=MRI assessment of cortical thickness and functional activity changes in adolescent girls following three months of practice on a visual-spatial task|journal=BMC Research Notes|year=2009|doi=10.1186/1756-0500-2-174|pmid=19723307|volume=2|page=174|pmc=2746806}}</ref> When first playing ''Tetris'', brain function and activity increases, along with greater cerebral energy consumption, measured by [[glucose]] metabolic rate. As ''Tetris'' players become more proficient, their brains show a reduced consumption of glucose, indicating more efficient brain activity for this task.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Haier RJ, Siegel BV, MacLachlan A, Soderling E, Lottenberg S, Buchsbaum MS|title=Regional glucose metabolic changes after learning a complex visuospatial/motor task: a positron emission tomographic study|journal=Brain Res.|volume=570|issue=1\u20132|pages=134\u201343|date=January 1992|pmid=1617405|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(92)90573-R}}</ref> Moderate play of ''Tetris'' (half-an-hour a day for three months) boosts general cognitive functions such as \"critical thinking, reasoning, language and processing\" and increases [[cerebral cortex]] thickness.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/6122290/Tetris-could-boost-brain-power.html Tetris 'could boost brain power'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212121948/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/6122290/Tetris-could-boost-brain-power.html |date=February 12, 2010 }} Telegraph news, September 2, 2009</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, an Oxford University research group headed by Dr. Emily Holmes reported in ''[[PLoS ONE]]'' that for healthy volunteers, playing ''Tetris'' soon after viewing traumatic material in the laboratory reduced the number of flashbacks to those scenes in the following week. They believe that the computer game may disrupt the memories that are retained of the sights and sounds witnessed at the time, and which are later re-experienced through involuntary, distressing flashbacks of that moment. The group hopes to develop this approach further as a potential intervention to reduce the flashbacks experienced in [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] but emphasized that these are only preliminary results.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Holmes EA|author2=James EL|author3=Coode-Bate T|author4=Deeprose C|title=Can playing the computer game \"Tetris\" reduce the build-up of flashbacks for trauma? A proposal from cognitive science|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=4|issue=1|pages= e4153|year=2009|pmid=19127289|pmc=2607539|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0004153|editor1-last=Bell|editor1-first=Vaughan|bibcode=2009PLoSO...4.4153H}}</ref>\n\nProfessor Jackie Andrade and Jon May, from [[Plymouth University]]'s Cognition Institute, and Ph.D. student Jessica Skorka-Brown have conducted research that shows that playing ''Tetris'' could distract from cravings and give a \"quick and manageable\" fix for people struggling to stick to diets, or quit smoking or drinking.<ref>{{cite news|last=GANDER|first=KASHMIRA|title=Playing Tetris could help with weight loss and smokers' cravings, psychologists claim|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/playing-tetris-could-help-with-weight-loss-and-smokers-cravings-psychologists-claim-9149045.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=February 24, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224123004/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/playing-tetris-could-help-with-weight-loss-and-smokers-cravings-psychologists-claim-9149045.html|archive-date=February 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnother notable effect is that, according to a Canadian study in April 2013, playing ''Tetris'' has been found to treat older adolescents with [[amblyopia]] (lazy eye), which was better than patching a victim's well eye to train their weaker eye. Dr. Robert Hess of the research team said: \"It's much better than patching \u2013 much more enjoyable; it's faster, and it seems to work better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/04/23/study-finds-tetris-effectively-treats-lazy-eye|title=A Study Find That ''Tetris'' Effectively Treats a Lazy Eye|author=Luke Karmali|website=[[IGN]]|date=April 23, 2013|accessdate=June 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620113327/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/04/23/study-finds-tetris-effectively-treats-lazy-eye|archive-date=June 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Tested in the [[United Kingdom]], this experiment also appears to help children with that problem.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-17616818|title=Video Game Treatment for a Lazy Eye|work=[[BBC News]]|date=April 4, 2012|accessdate=June 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819214014/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-17616818|archive-date=August 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game has been noted to cause the brain to involuntarily picture ''Tetris'' combinations even when the player is not playing (the [[Tetris effect|''Tetris'' effect]]), although this can occur with any computer game or situation showcasing repeated images or scenarios, such as a [[jigsaw puzzle]]. While debates about Tetris's cognitive benefits continue, at least some researchers view it as a milestone in the gamification of education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.elearninginside.com/game-changing-arrival-tetris-united-states/|title=It has been 30 years since Tetris arrived in the U.S.|date=January 29, 2018|work=eLearningInside News|access-date=November 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116085344/https://news.elearninginside.com/game-changing-arrival-tetris-united-states/|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Hasbro Games ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2018}}\nIn 2013, The Tetris Company signed a contract with Hasbro to make a [[Bop It]] and a [[Jenga]] themed version of ''Tetris''. The games were shown at the New York Toy Fair and Bop It Tetris was sold on Amazon.com in June 2013.\n\nJenga Tetris is like Jenga but using ''Tetris'' shapes.\n\nBop It Tetris is an [[audio game]]. It has several game modes including ''Marathon'' and ''Pass It''. In the Marathon Mode, the player has four lives and has to complete the puzzles with the square lights. The game unit has three actions which are: \"Slam It\" which slams the top part of the device down, \"Slide it\", a screen which can rotate from left and right, and \"Spin It\", where the device can spin. If the player fails to complete the puzzle, the voice of Buddy Rubino will make a [[Santa Claus]] type laugh and will encourage the player with a comment such as: \"Squares man! They're just squares!\" or \"Shapes are hard!\" and Buddy will then say \"Life lost\" and one of the four squares on the top screen will disappear. After every stage is completed Buddy will tell the player with a comment such as: \"Level up!\" and there will then be a 45-second bonus round which the player can score two or more bonus points.\n\nIn the Pass It Mode, it is the same as the Marathon mode except Buddy Rubino will say \"Pass It\" to let other people join in.\n\n== Reception and Legacy==\n{{Video game reviews\n| Allgame = Arcade: {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Cook|first=Brad|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2784&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114201703/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2784&tab=review|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 14, 2014|publisher=AllGame|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />C64: {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Sutyak|first=Jonathan|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16887&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004356/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16887&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />Macintosh: {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Savignano|first=Lisa Karen|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11800&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004358/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11800&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame|url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />NES&nbsp;(Tengen):&nbsp;{{Rating|4.5|5}}&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Skyler|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14911&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004353/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14911&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />NES&nbsp;(Nintendo):&nbsp;{{Rating|4.5|5}}&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web|last=Weiss|first=Brett Alan|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=1331&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216081022/http://allgame.com/game.php?id=1331&tab=review|archive-date=February 16, 2010|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| CVG = 94%<ref name=\"CVG-1989-review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4f2e51c9cdbbfbe/800/800 |title=Tetris Mastertronic |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |issue=92 |page=74 |date=June 1989 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032455/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4f2e51c9cdbbfbe/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| CRASH = 77%<ref name=\"Crash-19880review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/78d7602b35d0e2d/800/800 |title=Reviews: Tetris |magazine=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]] |issue=50 |page=10 |date=March 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032452/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/78d7602b35d0e2d/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| SUser = {{Rating|10|10}}<ref name=\"SinclairU-1988-review\">{{cite web |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/c53e67fb08dbe15/800/800 |title=TET\u042fIS: Arcade Review |magazine=[[Sinclair User]] |issue=1988 |page=13 |date=February 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032457/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/c53e67fb08dbe15/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| YSinclair = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Worrall|first=Tony|title=Tetris|url=http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/tetris.htm|publisher=The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years|accessdate=August 8, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427113515/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/tetris.htm|archivedate=April 27, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Zzap!64]]''\n| rev1Score = 98%<ref>{{cite web|title=Gold Standard|url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/zzap100/100thspec5.html|publisher=The Def Gui to Zzap!64|accessdate=August 8, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Dzo6NOv6?url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/zzap100/100thspec5.html|archive-date=January 28, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]]''\n| rev2Score = 95%<ref name=\"ACE-1988-review\">{{cite web |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4852d3d00d9894b/800/800 |title=Tetris: Can MIRRORSOFT pack them in? |publisher=[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]] |issue=5 |page=49 |date=February 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417035859/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4852d3d00d9894b/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| award1Pub = Zzap!64\n| award1 = Gold Medal\n| award2Pub = Sinclair User\n| award2 = SU Classic\n}}\n''[[Compute!]]'' called the IBM version of ''Tetris'' \"one of the most addictive computer games this side of the [[Berlin Wall]] ... [it] is ''not'' the game to start if you have work to do or an appointment to keep. Consider yourself warned\".<ref name=\"weatherman198807\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_098_1988_Jul#page/n73/mode/2up | title=Tetris | work=Compute! | date=July 1988 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | author=Weatherman, Lynne | page=72 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211621/https://archive.org/stream/1988-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_098_1988_Jul#page/n73/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[Orson Scott Card]] joked that the game \"proves that Russia still wants to [[We will bury you|bury us]]. I shudder to think of the blow to our economy as computer productivity drops to 0\". Noting that ''Tetris'' was not copy-protected, he wrote \"Obviously, the game is meant to find its way onto every American machine\".<ref name=\"card198904\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_107_1989_Apr#page/n11/mode/2up | title=Gameplay | work=Compute! | date=April 1989 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | author=Card, Orson Scott | page=11 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211723/https://archive.org/stream/1989-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_107_1989_Apr#page/n11/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The IBM version of the game was reviewed in 1988 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' No. 135 by Hartley, Patricia, and Kirk Lesser in \"The Role of Computers\" column. The reviewers gave the game 4.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Dragon135\">{{cite journal|title=The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|last2=Lesser|last3=Lesser|first1=Hartley|first2=Patricia|first3=Kirk|journal=Dragon|issue=135|date=July 1988|pages=82\u201389}}</ref> The Lessers later reviewed Spectrum HoloByte's [[Macintosh]] version of ''Tetris'' in 1989 in ''Dragon'' No. 141, giving that version 5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Dragon141\">{{cite journal|title= The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|last2=Lesser|last3=Lesser|first1=Hartley|first2=Patricia|first3=Kirk|journal=Dragon|issue=141|date= January 1989|pages=72\u201378}}</ref> ''[[Macworld]]'' reviewed the Macintosh version of ''Tetris'' in 1988, praising its stategic gameplay, stating that \"''Tetris'' offers the rare combination of being simple to learn but extremely challenging to play\", and also praising the inclusion of the [[Desk Accessory]] version, which uses less RAM. ''Macworld'' summarized their review by listing ''Tetris' ''pros and cons, stating that ''Tetris'' is \"Elegant; easy to play; challenging and addicting; requires quick thinking, long-term strategy, and lightning reflexes\" and listed ''Tetris''' cons as \"None.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last = Buderi|first = Robert|title = Tetris 1.0 Review|date = December 1988|url = https://archive.org/details/MacWorld_8812_December_1988/page/n181|magazine = Macworld|publisher = Mac Publishing|page = 178}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the ZX Spectrum version of the game was voted number 49 in the ''[[Your Sinclair]] Official Top 100 Games of All Time''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Top 100 Games of All Time|journal=Your Sinclair|date=September 1993}}</ref> In 1996, ''Tetris Pro'' was ranked the 38th best game of all time by ''[[Amiga Power]]''.<ref>Amiga Power magazine issue 64, Future Publishing, August 1996</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' picked the game as the #8 greatest game available in 1991, saying: \"Thanks to Nintendo\u2019s endless promotion, Tetris has become one of the most popular video games.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://ew.com/article/1991/11/22/video-games-guide/ | title=Video Games Guide | access-date=September 9, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219184932/http://ew.com/article/1991/11/22/video-games-guide/ | archive-date=February 19, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Computer Gaming World'' gave ''Tetris'' the 1989 Compute! Choice Award for Arcade Game, describing it as \"by far, the most addictive game ever\".<ref name=\"compute198901\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | title=The 189 Compute! Choice Awards | work=Compute! | date=January 1989 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | page=24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316200847/https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The game won three [[Software Publishers Association]] Excellence in Software Awards in 1989, including Best Entertainment Program and the Critic's Choice Award for consumers.<ref name=\"scisco198908\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_111_1989_Aug#page/n7/mode/2up | title=the Envelope, Please | work=Compute! | date=August 1989 | accessdate=November 11, 2013 | author=Scisco, Peter | page=6 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211940/https://archive.org/stream/1989-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_111_1989_Aug#page/n7/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Computer Gaming World'' in 1996 ranked it 14th on the magazine's list of the most innovative computer games.<ref name=\"cgw199611mostinnovative\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=The 15 Most Innovative Computer Games | work=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | accessdate=March 25, 2016 | pages=102 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408023915/http://cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | archive-date=April 8, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> That same year, ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' listed it as number 2 on their \"Top 100 Games of All Time\", commenting that, \"There is something so perfect, so [[Zen]] about the falling blocks of ''Tetris'' that the game has captured the interest of everyone who has ever played it.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Top 100 Games of All Time |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|page=71}}</ref> On March 12, 2007, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that ''Tetris'' was named to a list of the ten most important video games of all time, the so-called [[game canon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/12/arts/design/12vide.html?ex=1331352000&en=380fc9bb18694da5&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|title=Is That Just Some Game? No, It's a Cultural Artifact|newspaper=[[nytimes.com]]|first=HEATHER|last=CHAPLIN|date=March 12, 2007|accessdate=November 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204212137/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/12/arts/design/12vide.html?ex=1331352000&en=380fc9bb18694da5&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|archive-date=December 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> After announced at the 2007 [[Game Developers Conference]], the [[Library of Congress]] took up the video game preservation proposal and began with these 10 games, including ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"Joystiq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2007/03/12/10-most-important-video-games-of-all-time-as-judged-by-2-design/ |title=10 most important video games of all time, as judged by 2 designers, 2 academics, and 1 lowly blogger |last=Ransom-Wiley |first=James |publisher=Joystiq |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422035847/http://www.joystiq.com/2007/03/12/10-most-important-video-games-of-all-time-as-judged-by-2-design/ |archivedate=April 22, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/09/yes-the-library-of-congress-has-video-games-an-interview-with-david-gibson/ |title=Yes, The Library of Congress Has Video Games: An Interview with David Gibson |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=January 18, 2013 |publisher=blogs.loc.gov |first=Trevor |last=Owens |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205100245/http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/09/yes-the-library-of-congress-has-video-games-an-interview-with-david-gibson/ |archivedate=December 5, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, video game website [[GameFAQs]] hosted its sixth annual \"[[GameFAQs#Contests|Character Battle]]\", in which the users nominate their favorite video game characters for a popularity contest in which characters participate. The L-shaped ''Tetris'' piece (or \"L-Block\" as it was called) entered the contest as a joke character, but on November 4, 2007, it won the contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/cb6|title=Fall 2007: The Great GameFAQs Character Battle VI|website=GameFAQs|accessdate=November 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029201304/http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/cb6|archive-date=October 29, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 6, 2009, Google honored ''Tetris''{{'}} 25-year anniversary by changing its logotype to a version drawn with ''Tetris'' blocks \u2013 the \"l\" letter being the long ''Tetris'' block lowering into its place,<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Features TETRIS Look For Game's 25th Anniversary|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090605005609/en|publisher=Electronic Arts|date=June 5, 2009|quote=Google will roll out the TETRIS-inspired design in 24-hour periods, starting first at 1:00&nbsp;pm EDT in Japan, Australia, and New Zealand. From 6:00&nbsp;pm&nbsp; \u2013 7:00&nbsp;pm EDT, the TETRIS-inspired design will begin appearing in Europe, Asia, Africa, and the Middle East. Starting June 6th, at 12:00&nbsp;am EDT, the TETRIS-inspired design will be available in North and South America.|accessdate=September 25, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110216141150/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090605005609/en|archive-date=February 16, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> seen here.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/25-years-of-tetris-courtesy-of-tetris-holding-llc |title=25 Years of Tetris \u2013 courtesy of Tetris Holding, LLC |date=June 6, 2009 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104165253/http://www.google.com/doodles/25-years-of-tetris-courtesy-of-tetris-holding-llc |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, ''[[Game Informer]]'' put ''Tetris'' 3rd on their list of \"The Top 200 Games of All Time\", saying that \"If a game could be considered ageless, it's ''Tetris''\".<ref name=\"gi_best\">{{cite journal|author=The ''Game Informer'' staff|title=The Top 200 Games of All Time|pages=44\u201379|issue= 200|date=December 2009|journal=Game Informer|issn=1067-6392|oclc=27315596}}</ref> The ''Game Informer'' staff also placed it third on their 2001 list of the 100 best games ever.<ref>{{cite web |title=Game Informer's Top 100 Games of All Time (Circa Issue 100) |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx |work=[[Game Informer]] |last=Cork |first=Jeff |date=November 16, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100408113757/http://gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx |archive-date=April 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''{{'}}s 100th issue had ''Tetris'' as first place in the \"100 Best Games of All Time\", commenting that \"''Tetris'' is as pure as a video game can get. ... When the right blocks come your way - and if you can manage to avoid mistakes - the game can be relaxing. One mislaid block, however, and your duties switch to damage control, a mad, panicky dash to clean up your mess or die.\" ''Tetris'' was also the only game for which the list did not specify one or two versions; the editors explained that after deadlocking over which version was best, they concluded that there was no wrong version of ''Tetris'' to play.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=100 Best Games of All Time |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=100 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=November 1997|page=160}} Note: Contrary to the title, the intro to the article (on page 100) explicitly states that the list covers console video games only, meaning PC games and arcade games were not eligible.</ref> In 2007, ''Tetris'' came in second place in [[IGN]]'s \"100 Greatest Video Games of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_2.html |title=IGN Top 100 Games of All Time \u2013 2007 |publisher=Top100.ign.com |date= |accessdate=November 22, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107133844/http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_2.html|archivedate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> In January 2010, it was announced that the [[List of Tetris variants|''Tetris'' franchise]] had sold more than 170 million copies, approximately 70 million physical copies and over 100 million copies [[Tetris (Electronic Arts)|for cell phones]],<ref name=guardian020609>''[[The Guardian]]'', June 2, 2009, [https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov How Tetris conquered the world, block by block] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329135242/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov |date=March 29, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maximejohnson.com/techno/2010/01/tetris-atteint-les-100-millions-de-telechargements-payants-et-une-petite-histoire-du-jeu/ |title=\u00bb Tetris atteint les 100 millions de t\u00e9l\u00e9chargements payants (et une petite histoire du jeu) \u2013 Maximejohnson.com/techno : actualit\u00e9s technologiques, tests et opinions par le j |publisher=Maximejohnson.com |date=January 19, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726141129/http://www.maximejohnson.com/techno/2010/01/tetris-atteint-les-100-millions-de-telechargements-payants-et-une-petite-histoire-du-jeu/ |archive-date=July 26, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> making it one of the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchises of all time]]. {{As of|2011|12}}, ''Tetris'' has sold 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads.<ref>{{cite news |title=EA Launches New Tetris\u00ae Game on the App Store Today |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111201006159/en/EA-Launches-New-Tetris%C2%AE-Game-App-Store |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, ''[[PC Format]]'' named ''Tetris'' one of the 50 best computer games ever. The editors called it \"incredibly addictive\" and \"one of the best games of all time\".<ref name=pcformat50>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[PC Format]] | title=The 50 best games EVER! |date=October 1991 | issue=1 | pages=109\u2013111 }}</ref>\n\n''[[Guinness World Records]]'' has recognized the game as being the most ported in the history of video gaming, appearing on in excess of 65 different platforms by 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/most-ported-computer-game/ |title=Most ported computer game |publisher=Guinnessworldrecords.com |date=October 1, 2010 |accessdate=June 7, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223258/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/most-ported-computer-game/ |archive-date=December 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThere was a hoax that circulated in February 2019 that the original NES instruction manual for ''Tetris'' had named the seven tetrominos with names like \"Orange Ricky\", \"Hero\" and \"Smashboy\", but was disproven. Despite being disproven by video game historians, a question on the October 7, 2019 airing of ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' alluded to these names.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/jeopardy-airs-a-hilariously-incorrect-bit-of-tetris-tr-1838889592 | title = Jeopardy! Airs A Hilariously Incorrect Bit Of Tetris Trivia | first = Chris | last = Kohler | date = October 8, 2019 | accessdate = October 8, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\n=== In research ===\n''Tetris'' has been the subject of academic research. [[Vladimir Pokhilko]] was the first clinical psychologist to conduct experiments using ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"MarkWolf2012\">{{cite book | author=Mark J. P. Wolf | title=Encyclopedia of Video Games: The Culture, Technology, and Art of Gaming | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=deBFx7QAwsQC&pg=PA642 | accessdate=February 5, 2013 | date=August 31, 2012 | publisher=ABC-CLIO | isbn=978-0-313-37936-9 | page=642 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528022924/http://books.google.com/books?id=deBFx7QAwsQC&pg=PA642 | archive-date=May 28, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, it has been used for research in several fields including the [[theory of computation]], algorithmic theory, and [[cognitive psychology]].\n\nDuring the game of ''Tetris'', blocks appear to [[Adsorption|adsorb]] onto the lower surface of the window. This has led scientists to use tetrominoes \"as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape\" to model their \"[[adsorption]] on a flat surface\" to study the [[thermodynamics]] of [[nanoparticles]].<ref>[https://arstechnica.com/science/news/2009/05/the-thermodynamics-of-tetris.ars The Thermodynamics of Tetiris] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912220000/http://arstechnica.com/science/news/2009/05/the-thermodynamics-of-tetris.ars |date=September 12, 2011 }}, Ars Technica, 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1021/la900196b| pmid=19397254|title = Structure, Thermodynamics, and Solubility in Tetromino Fluids| journal=Langmuir| volume=25| issue=12| pages=6702\u20136716|year = 2009|last1 = Barnes|first1 = Brian C.| last2=Siderius| first2=Daniel W.| last3=Gelb| first3=Lev D.}}</ref>\n\n== Film ==\n[[Threshold Entertainment]] has teamed up with The Tetris Company to develop a film adaptation of ''Tetris''. Threshold's CEO describes the film as an epic sci-fi adventure that will form part of a trilogy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/tetris-movie-story|title='Tetris' Movie Planned as an Epic Sci-Fi Adventure|work=Movieweb|date=September 30, 2014|accessdate=September 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001011505/http://www.movieweb.com/tetris-movie-story|archive-date=October 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tetris-movie-be-80m-us-894779|title='Tetris' Movie to Be $80M U.S.-China Co-Production|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Brzeski|first=Patrick|date=May 17, 2016|access-date=May 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518095550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tetris-movie-be-80m-us-894779|archive-date=May 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, sources reported on a press release claiming the film would be shot in China in 2017 with an $80 million budget. However, no 2017 or later sources confirm the film ever actually went into production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2016/05/17/tetris-movie-real/|title=Is this 'Tetris' movie for real? Too many key blocks are missing to be sure|last=Dickey|first=Josh|date=May 17, 2016|publisher=Mashable|access-date=June 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624093105/https://mashable.com/2016/05/17/tetris-movie-real/|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Tetris'' appeared in the 2010 short animated film [[Pixels (2010 film)|''Pixels'']], and in the 2015 movie ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'' inspired by the former.<ref>{{Citation|title=Pixels (2015)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2120120/movieconnections|accessdate=February 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118041924/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2120120/movieconnections|archive-date=November 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Video Games|1980s|1990s}}\n* ''[[Pentomino]]'' [[tiling puzzle]]s and games are popular in [[recreational mathematics]].\n* ''[[Brain Wall]]'' and ''[[Blokken]]'' \u2014 game shows based on ''Tetris''\n* ''[[Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters]]'' \u2014 2011 documentary about the 2010 ''Tetris'' Championships featuring interviews with Pajitnov and Dr. Richard Haier.\n* ''[[Game Over (book)|Game Over]]'' \u2014 1993 book covering Nintendo history, including interviews with Alexey Pajitnov and others regarding ''Tetris'' licensing.\n* [[List of Tetris variants|List of ''Tetris'' variants]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web | url = http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm | title = Tetris Story | last = Gerasimov | first = Vadim | website = [[Vadim Gerasimov|OverSigma]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/mathematicians-prove-tetr/ | title = Mathematicians Prove Tetris Is Tough | last = Graham | first = Sarah | date = October 29, 2002 | website = [[Scientific American]]}}\n* {{cite AV media | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00mdqf8 | title = The creation of Tetris | date = December 29, 2012 | website = [[BBC World Service]] | publisher = [[BBC]]}}\n* {{IMDb title|0409371|Tetris: From Russia with Love}}\n* {{IMDb title|1836974|Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Books===\n* {{Cite book |last1=Loguidice |first1=Bill |last2=Barton |first2=Matt |year=2009 |title=Vintage Games: An Insider Look at the History of the Most Influential Games of All Time |url=https://www.routledge.com/Vintage-Games-An-Insider-Look-at-the-History-of-Grand-Theft-Auto-Super/Loguidice-Barton/p/book/9780240811468 |edition=1st |publisher=[[Focal Press]] |pages=291\u2013301 |isbn=0240811461}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Kent |first=Steven |title=The Ultimate History of Video Games: From Pong to Pokemon: The Story Behind the Craze That Touched Our Lives and Changed the World |publisher=Three Rivers Press |year=2001 |edition=1st |pages=377-381 |isbn=9780761536437}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Sheff |first1=David |last2=Eddy |first2=Andy |title=Game Over: Press Start to Continue |publisher=Cyberactive Media Group |year=1999 |edition=1st |pages=295-348 |isbn=0966961706}} \n* {{Cite book |last=Trefry |first=Gregory |title=Casual Game Design: Designing Play for the Gamer in All of Us |publisher=CRC Press |year=2010 |pages=179-185 |isbn=0123749530 |url=https://www.crcpress.com/Casual-Game-Design-Designing-Play-for-the-Gamer-in-ALL-of-Us/T